\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
A Celestial Description of Planar Yang-Mills Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Igor Mol
\end_layout

\begin_layout Affiliation
Federal University of Juiz de Fora 
\begin_inset Formula $-$
\end_inset

 Departament of Mathematics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Affiliation
Federal University of Minas Gerais 
\begin_inset Formula $-$
\end_inset

 Instituto de Ciências Exatas (ICEx)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author Email
igormol@ime.unicamp.br
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Continuing our program of deriving aspects of celestial holography from string theory,
 we extend the Roiban-Spradlin-Volovich-Witten (RSVW) formalism to celestial amplitudes.
 We reformulate the tree-level maximally-helicity-violating (MHV) celestial leaf amplitudes for gluons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 supersymmetric Yang-Mills (SYM) theory and for gravitons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity in terms of 
\emph on
minitwistor wavefunctions
\emph default
.
 These are defined as representatives of cohomology classes on the minitwistor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

,
 associated to the three-dimensional Euclidean anti-de Sitter space.
 In this framework,
 celestial leaf amplitudes are expressed as integrals over the moduli space of minitwistor lines.
 We construct a minitwistor generating functional for MHV leaf amplitudes using the Quillen determinant line bundle,
 extending the approach originally developed by Boels,
 Mason and Skinner.
 Building on this formalism,
 we propose supersymmetric celestial conformal field theories (CFTs) as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-models,
 where the worldsheet is given by the celestial supersphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1|2}$
\end_inset

,
 and the target space is the minitwistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

.
 We demonstrate that the semiclassical effective action of these 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-models reproduces the MHV gluonic and gravitational leaf amplitudes in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM theory and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity.
 This construction provides a concrete realisation of the supersymmetric celestial CFT framework recently introduced by Tropper (2024).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "adamo2013moduli"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset toc
LatexCommand tableofcontents

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An open problem in high-energy theoretical physics is the dynamical derivation of the celestial holography dictionary,
 which posits that the physics of asymptotically flat spacetimes can be encoded in a conjectured celestial conformal field theory (CCFT) living on the celestial sphere.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplicity of gauge-theory scattering amplitudes for gluons in maximally-helicity-violating (MHV) configurations,
 described by the Parke-Taylor formula,
 led Nair to reinterpret these amplitudes as correlation functions of a Wess-Zumino-Novikov-Witten (WZNW) current algebra on the Riemann sphere,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 This viewpoint motivated the development of twistor and ambitwistor string theories and,
 later,
 the Cachazo-He-Yuan (CHY) formalism.
 Here,
 we ask whether a similar,
 bottom-up approach can yield concrete dynamical models for CCFTs.
 Such models may describe realistic physical theories or,
 at least,
 specific sectors thereof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Minitwistor Superwavefunctions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Review:
 Twistor Superwavefunctions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 supersymmetric twistor wavefunction for gluons,
 labelled by the scaling weight 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

,
 defines a Dolbeault cohomology class:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[f^{w}]\,\in\,H^{0,1}\big(\mathbf{PT}^{3|4},\mathcal{O}\left(-w\right)\big).
\]

\end_inset

Introduce homogeneous coordinates:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{Z}^{I}\,\coloneqq\,\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha}\big)
\]

\end_inset

on projective twistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{PT}^{3|4}\subset\mathbf{CP}^{3|4}$
\end_inset

.
 The dual (momentum-twistor) coordinates are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{W}^{I}\,\coloneqq\,\big(\nu^{A},\bar{\nu}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big).
\]

\end_inset

We employ abstract index notation with 
\begin_inset Formula $I,I',...\in\{A,\dot{A},\alpha\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The twistor superwavefunction is explicitly given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f^{w}\big(\mathcal{Z}^{I};\mathcal{W}^{I'}\big)\,\coloneqq\,\underset{\mathbf{C}^{*}\,\,\,}{\int}\,\frac{dt}{t}\,t^{w}\,\,\,\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(\nu^{A}-t\lambda^{A}\big)\exp\big(it\,([\mu\bar{\nu}]+\psi\cdot\eta)\big)\,.\label{eq:-27}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here the spinorial delta function is defined by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}^{2}\left(\sigma^{A}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\frac{1}{\left(2\pi i\right)^{2}}\,\bigwedge_{A\in\{1,2\}}\,\overline{\partial}\,\,\,\frac{1}{\sigma^{A}}\,\,\,,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $[\sigma^{A}]$
\end_inset

 denote homogeneous coordinates on the projective line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To obtain a more explicit representation,
 introduce an auxiliary spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota^{A}$
\end_inset

,
 chosen arbitrarily but non-vanishing.
 Using the Green's function for the Dolbeault operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\partial}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

,
 one shows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}^{2}\left(z^{A}-t\lambda^{A}\right)\,=\,\frac{1}{\left(2\pi i\right)^{2}}\,\bigwedge_{A\in\{1,2\}}\,\overline{\partial}\,\,\,\frac{1}{z^{A}-t\lambda^{A}}\,=\,\overline{\delta}\left(t-\frac{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }\right)\,\overline{\delta}\left(\left\langle \lambda z\right\rangle \right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Substituting this into Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-27"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) gives the explicit gluonic superwavefunction:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f^{p}\big(\mathcal{Z}^{I};\mathcal{W}^{I'}\big)=\overline{\delta}\left(\left\langle \lambda z\right\rangle \right)\left(\frac{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }\right)^{p-1}\,\exp\left(i\frac{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }\,\left(\,s[\mu\bar{z}]+\psi\cdot\eta\,\right)\right).\label{eq:-28}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next,
 define the 
\emph on
projective delta function
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 with conformal weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}\big(z^{A},\lambda^{A}\big)\,\coloneqq\,\frac{1}{\left(2\pi i\right)^{2}}\,\underset{\mathbf{C}^{*}}{\int}\,\frac{dt}{t}\,\,\,t^{\Delta}\,\bigwedge_{A\in\{1,2\}}\,\overline{\partial}\,\,\,\frac{1}{z^{A}-t\lambda^{A}}\,=\,\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}\left(\left\langle \lambda z\right\rangle \right)\left(\frac{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }\right)^{\Delta-1}.\label{eq:-35}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Using this identity,
 Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-28"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) simplifies to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f^{p}\big(\mathcal{Z}^{I};\mathcal{W}^{I'}\big)\,=\,\overline{\delta}_{p}\left(z,\lambda\right)\,\exp\left(i\frac{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }\,\left(s[\mu\bar{z}]+\psi\cdot\eta\right)\right).\label{eq:-154}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Minitwistor Superwavefunctions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To construct the celestial superwavefunction for gluons in the minitwistor-superspace formalism,
 we introduce a normalised spinor basis:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z^{A}\,\coloneqq\,\left(1,-\zeta\right),\,\,\,\bar{z}_{\dot{A}}\,\coloneqq\,(1,-\bar{\zeta}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}$
\end_inset

 are holomorphic and antiholomorphic coordinates on the celestial sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{CS}\simeq\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the gluonic superwavefunction (Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-154"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

)),
 we make the substitutions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nu^{A}\,\mapsto\,z^{A},\,\,\,\bar{\nu}_{\dot{A}}\,\mapsto\,s\cdot\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a real,
 nonnegative parameter encoding the gluon's frequency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the viewpoint of celestial CFT,
 a gluon state is entirely specified by three data:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The celestial conformal weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The helicity,
 encoded by the Grassmann variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1,...,4$
\end_inset

 labelling the supersymmetry generators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The insertion point on the celestial sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{CS}$
\end_inset

,
 given by the normalised spinor basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}}\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
minitwistor superwavefunction
\emph default
 associated with a gluon of conformal weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 and configuration 
\begin_inset Formula $\{z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\}$
\end_inset

 is defined by the half-Mellin transform:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha};z^{A},\bar{z}_{A},\eta^{\alpha}\big)\,\coloneqq\,\underset{\mathbf{R}_{+}}{\int}\,\frac{ds}{s}\,\,\,s^{\Delta}\,f^{p}\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha};z^{A},s\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Substituting the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{p}$
\end_inset

 from Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-27"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) yields the double-integral representation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big)\,=\,\underset{\mathbf{R}_{+}}{\int}\,\frac{ds}{s}\,s^{\Delta}\,\underset{\mathbf{C}^{*}\,\,\,}{\int}\,\frac{dt}{t}\,t^{p}\,\,\,\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(z^{A}-t\lambda^{A}\big)\,\exp\big(it\,(s[\mu\bar{z}]+\psi\cdot\eta)\big)\,\label{eq:}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Homogeneity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The affine and Mellin integrals make explicit the homogeneous transformation properties of the superwavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}$
\end_inset

.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1},t_{2}\in\mathbf{C}^{*}$
\end_inset

,
 one has:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\big(t_{1}\cdot\lambda^{A},t_{2}\cdot\mu_{\dot{A}},t_{1}\cdot\psi^{\alpha};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big)\,=\,t_{1}^{\Delta-p}\,t_{2}^{-\Delta}\,\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha};z^{a},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big),\label{eq:-29}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha};t_{1}\cdot z^{A},t_{2}\cdot\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},t_{1}^{-1}\cdot\eta^{\alpha}\big)\,=\,t_{1}^{p-\Delta-2}\,t_{2}^{-\Delta}\,\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big).\label{eq:-30}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These homogeneity laws suggest that 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 may be regarded as dual to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 This interpretation will be justified when we introduce the minitwistor transform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-29"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 the Grassmann-odd coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 scales like 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 transform as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda^{A}\,\mapsto\,t_{1}\cdot\lambda^{A},\,\,\,\mu_{\dot{A}}\,\mapsto\,t_{2}\cdot\mu_{\dot{A}},\,\,\,\psi^{\alpha}\,\mapsto\,t_{1}\cdot\psi^{\alpha}.\label{eq:-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By contrast,
 Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-30"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 transforms inversely to 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{A}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 obey:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z^{A}\,\mapsto\,t_{1}\cdot z^{A},\,\,\,\bar{z}_{\dot{A}}\,\mapsto\,t_{2}\cdot\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\,\,\,\eta^{\alpha}\,\mapsto\,t_{1}^{-1}\cdot\eta^{\alpha}.\label{eq:-31}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Explicit Form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Performing the affine and Mellin integrals in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\big(\mathsf{Z}^{I};\mathsf{W}^{I'}\big)\,=\,\overline{\delta}\left(\left\langle \lambda z\right\rangle \right)\left(\frac{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }\right)^{p-\Delta-1}\frac{\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)}{[\mu\bar{z}]^{\Delta}}\exp\left(i\frac{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }\psi\cdot\eta\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Alternatively,
 one may invoke the projective delta function 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 (Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-35"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

)).
 In this notation,
 the superwavefunction simplifies to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\big(\mathsf{Z}^{I};\mathsf{W}^{I'}\big)\,=\,\overline{\delta}_{p-\Delta}\left(z,\lambda\right)\frac{\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)}{[\mu\bar{z}]^{\Delta}}\exp\left(i\frac{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }\psi\cdot\eta\right).\label{eq:-39}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This form will prove useful when deriving the bulk-to-boundary propagator on the 
\begin_inset Formula $(3|8)$
\end_inset

-dimensional Euclidean anti-de Sitter space.
 This derivation proceeds via the Penrose integral-geometric transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To establish completeness and orthogonality of the family 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\}$
\end_inset

,
 we introduce the conjugate wavefunction:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{\Psi}_{\Delta}^{p}\big(\mathsf{Z}^{I};\mathsf{W}^{I'}\big)\,\coloneqq\,\overline{\delta}_{p-\Delta}\left(z,\lambda\right)\frac{\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)}{[\bar{z}\mu]^{\Delta}}\exp\left(-i\frac{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }\psi\cdot\eta\right).\label{eq:-41}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Under conjugation,
 the phase in the exponential changes sign.
 The denominator ordering also changes from 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mu\bar{z}]$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $[\bar{z}\mu]$
\end_inset

.
 The latter condition simplifies the proportionality factors in the resulting completeness and orthogonality relations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Homogeneous Bundles on Minitwistor Superspace
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the preceding subsection,
 we derived an explicit formula for the minitwistor superwavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}(\mathsf{W}^{I};\mathsf{Z}^{I'})$
\end_inset

 by applying the Mellin transform to the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 supersymmetric twistor wavefunction.
 We now interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}$
\end_inset

 geometrically.
 It defines a section (more precisely a 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

-current) on the minitwistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 (see Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Minitwistor-Superspace"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a dual minitwistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

,
 which is canonically isomorphic to the holomorphic celestial supersphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{CS}\simeq\mathbf{CP}^{1|4}$
\end_inset

 (Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Dual-Minitwistor-Superspace"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Equivalently,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

 serves as a parameter space for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{CS}$
\end_inset

.
 The minitwistor transform then carries sections of holomorphic bundles over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 to sections over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This transform is our prescription for converting sectional (or leaf) amplitudes into minitwistor amplitudes.
 It thereby provides a geometric reinterpretation of celestial amplitudes as semiclassical expectation values of Wilson line operators,
 or alternatively as correlation functions in the minitwistor sigma-model.
 In this sense,
 the minitwistor superspace geometry offers a dual description of the flat-space hologram on the celestial supersphere,
 much as the Fourier transform relates position and momentum representations in elementary quantum mechanics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Minitwistor Superspace
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Minitwistor-Superspace"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}\subset\bigtimes^{2}\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 denote the bosonic minitwistor space of three-dimensional Euclidean anti-de Sitter space.
 We begin by defining the ordinary 
\begin_inset Formula $(2|4)$
\end_inset

-dimensional minitwistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 This supermanifold is obtained by enforcing the transformation laws of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-1"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) as a symmetry group on its underlying (projective) geometry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Introduce the vector superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}\simeq\mathbf{C}^{4|4}$
\end_inset

 with Cartesian coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{W}^{I}\,\coloneqq\,\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha}\big)$
\end_inset

.
 On 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{U}\coloneqq\mathbf{V}-\{0\}$
\end_inset

,
 impose the equivalence relation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha}\big)\,\sim\,\big(t_{1}\cdot\lambda^{A},t_{2}\cdot\mu_{\dot{A}},t_{1}\cdot\psi^{\alpha}\big),\quad\forall\,t_{1},t_{2}\in\mathbf{C}^{*}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Define the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
minitwistor superspace 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 as the set of equivalence classes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{w}\coloneqq[\mathsf{W}^{I}]\in\mathbf{U}/\sim$
\end_inset

 subject to the non-degeneracy condition:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[\lambda^{\flat}\mu]\neq0,\quad\big(\lambda^{\flat}\big)_{\dot{A}}\coloneqq\big(\lambda^{A}\big)^{*};
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and equip it with the quotient topology.
 This condition ensures nontrivial Dolbeault cohomology on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

,
 so that minitwistor superwavefunctions are realised as its cohomology representatives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Quotient Map.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi_{0}:\mathbf{M}\longrightarrow\mathbf{MT}_{s},\quad\mathsf{W}^{I}\mapsto\mathsf{w}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

the natural quotient map,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{w}=[\mathsf{W}^{I}]$
\end_inset

.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}\subset\mathbf{U}$
\end_inset

 is the maximal open submanifold on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Its boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\mathbf{U}}\mathbf{M}$
\end_inset

 consists of those equivalence classes 
\begin_inset Formula $[(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha})]$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $[\lambda^{\flat}\mu]=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 will henceforth be called
\emph on
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

-graded minitwistors
\emph default
 and denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{w},\mathsf{w}'$
\end_inset

,
 etc.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{w}\in\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

,
 we refer to a choice of preimage 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{W}^{I}\in\pi_{0}^{-1}(\mathsf{w})$
\end_inset

 as a 
\emph on
coordinate representative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Orientation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To specify the orientation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

,
 first introduce the holomorphic and antiholomorphic forms:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D\lambda\,\coloneqq\,\varepsilon_{AB}\lambda^{A}d\lambda^{B},\,\,\,D\mu\,\coloneqq\,\varepsilon^{\dot{A}\dot{B}}\mu_{\dot{A}}d\mu_{\dot{B}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and let 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{0|4}\psi$
\end_inset

 denote the Berezin measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}^{0|4}$
\end_inset

.
 The natural volume form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

-graded measure:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}\,\coloneqq\,D\lambda\wedge D\mu\wedge d^{0|4}\psi.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Under the rescaling of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-1"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 one finds:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}\,\mapsto\,t_{1}^{-2}t_{2}^{2}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Dual Minitwistor Superspace
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Dual-Minitwistor-Superspace"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second set of transformation rules,
 stated in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-31"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 motivates the introduction of the 
\emph on
dual minitwistor superspace
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 We will show in our discussion of scattering amplitudes that this dual space is intimately connected to the holomorphic celestial supersphere.
 Indeed,
 each point of the celestial supersphere corresponds to a point in the dual minitwistor superspace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The minitwistor transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{MT}$
\end_inset

 then carries sections over the dual superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

 to sections over the original minitwistor supermanifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 This operation is 
\emph on
analogous 
\emph default
to the ordinary Fourier transform in quantum mechanics,
 which maps wavefunctions from the position representation to the momentum representation.
 In our framework,
 
\emph on
the minitwistor superspace geometry provides a dual description of the flat-space hologram.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin by defining the dual vector superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}^{*}\simeq\big(\mathbf{C}^{4|4}\big)^{*}$
\end_inset

 with dual coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Z}^{I}=(z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{z}_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 will serve as the van der Waerden spinors parametrising the holomorphic celestial sphere.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{U}^{*}\coloneqq\mathbf{V}^{*}-\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 On 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{U}^{*}$
\end_inset

 impose the equivalence relation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\big(z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big)\,\simeq\,\big(t_{1}\cdot z^{A},t_{2}\cdot\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},t_{1}^{-1}\cdot\eta^{\alpha}\big),\quad\forall\,t_{1},t_{2}\in\mathbf{C}^{*}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The 
\emph on
dual minitwistor superspace
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is then the set of equivalence classes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{z}\coloneqq[\mathsf{Z}^{I}]\in\mathbf{U}^{*}\boldsymbol{\big/}\simeq$
\end_inset

 subject to the non-degeneracy condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[z^{\flat}\bar{z}]\;\neq\;0,\quad\big(z^{\flat}\big)_{\dot{A}}\;\coloneqq\;\big(z^{A}\big)^{*};
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and endowed with the quotient topology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Quotient map.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In what follows,
 we denote by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi_{0}^{*}\colon\mathbf{M}^{*}\boldsymbol{\longrightarrow}\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*},\quad\mathsf{Z}^{I}\mapsto\mathsf{z}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

the quotient map,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{z}=[\mathsf{Z}^{I}]$
\end_inset

.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}^{*}\subset\mathbf{U}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is the maximal open submanifold on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{0}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Its boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\mathbf{U}^{*}}\mathbf{M}^{*}$
\end_inset

 consists of those equivalence classes 
\begin_inset Formula $[(z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha})]$
\end_inset

 for which the non-degeneracy condition is violated,
 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $[z^{\flat}\bar{z}]=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Points of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

 are denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{z},\mathsf{z}',\dots$
\end_inset

 and are called 
\emph on
dual 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

-graded minitwistors
\emph default
.
 Any lift 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Z}^{I}\in(\pi_{0}^{*})^{-1}(\mathsf{z})$
\end_inset

 is referred to as a 
\emph on
coordinate representative
\emph default
 of the dual minitwistor point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{z}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Volume superform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To fix the orientation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

,
 first introduce the standard holomorphic and anti-holomorphic measures on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Dz\,\coloneqq\,\varepsilon_{AB}z^{A}dz^{B},\,\,\,D\bar{z}\,\coloneqq\,\varepsilon^{\dot{A}\dot{B}}\bar{z}_{\dot{A}}d\bar{z}_{\dot{B}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{0|4}\eta$
\end_inset

 denote the Berezin measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}^{0|4}$
\end_inset

.
 The resulting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

-graded volume form is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D^{2|4}\mathsf{Z}\,\coloneqq\,Dz\wedge D\bar{z}\wedge d^{0|4}\eta.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Under the scaling of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-31"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 one finds:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D^{2|4}\mathsf{Z}\,\mapsto\,t_{1}^{6}t_{2}^{2}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{Z}.\label{eq:-38}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{A}(p,q)$
\end_inset

-bundle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now introduce a two-parameter family of holomorphic vector bundles whose sections model the physical fields and the minitwistor superwavefunctions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{A}(p,q)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fix 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q\in\mathbf{Z}$
\end_inset

 and a normed algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 selected according to the desired background field or superwavefunction.
 Define the auxiliary trivial bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}\coloneqq\mathbf{M}\times A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}$
\end_inset

,
 impose the following equivalence relation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha},|a\rangle\big)\,\equiv_{p,q}\,\big(t_{1}\cdot\lambda^{A},t_{2}\cdot\mu_{\dot{A}},t_{1}\cdot\psi^{\alpha},t_{1}^{p}t_{2}^{q}\cdot|a\rangle\big),\quad\forall\,t_{1},t_{2}\in\mathbf{C}_{*}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The total space of our bundle is then the quotient:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{O}_{A}(p,q)\,\coloneqq\,\mathbf{E}\boldsymbol{\big/}\equiv_{p,q},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the natural projection 
\begin_inset Formula $Q:\mathbf{E}\longrightarrow\mathcal{O}_{A}(p,q)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Fibration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{pr}_{\mathbf{M}}:\mathbf{E}\longrightarrow\mathbf{M}$
\end_inset

 be the projection onto the first factor and define the surjection
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{0}:\mathbf{E}\longrightarrow\mathbf{MT}_{s},\quad Q_{0}\coloneqq\pi_{0}\circ\text{pr}_{\mathbf{M}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By construction,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{w}\in\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

-graded minitwistor point and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{W}^{I}\in\pi_{0}^{-1}(\mathsf{w})$
\end_inset

 any coordinate representative,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}\big(\mathsf{W}^{I},|a\rangle\big)=\mathsf{w}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $|a\rangle\in A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next,
 consider the quotient manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{A}(p,q)$
\end_inset

.
 We endow it with the structure of a holomorphic vector bundle over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 by introducing the projection 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi:\mathcal{O}_{A}(p,q)\longrightarrow\mathbf{MT}_{s}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This bundle map is uniquely determined by the condition that the quotient map 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}$
\end_inset

 lifts to 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently,
 the following diagram commutes:
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation} 
\backslash
label{eq:comm-diagram-modified} 
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[   row sep=2cm,
   column sep=2cm,
   arrows={shorten <=4pt,
 shorten >=4pt},
   every label/.append style={font=} ]   & 
\backslash
mathbf{E}     
\backslash
arrow[dl,
 "Q"']     
\backslash
arrow[dr,
 "Q_0"]   & 
\backslash

\backslash
   
\backslash
mathcal{O}_A(p,q)     
\backslash
arrow[rr,
 "{
\backslash
pi}"{swap,yshift=-5pt}]   & & 
\backslash
mathbf{MT} 
\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{equation} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

Hence one has the relation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi\circ Q=Q_{0}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Module of Sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We next characterise the sections of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{A}(p,q)\stackrel{\pi}{\to}\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 A map
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a:\mathbf{M}\longrightarrow A,\quad\mathsf{W}^{I}\mapsto|a(\mathsf{W}^{I})\rangle
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is called an 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-valued homogeneous function of bi-degree 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,q)$
\end_inset


\emph default
 if the following holds.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{W}^{I}=(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 and,
 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1},t_{2}\in\mathbf{C}_{*}$
\end_inset

,
 define the rescaled coordinates
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathsf{W}'^{I}\coloneqq\big(t_{1}\cdot\lambda^{A},t_{2}\cdot\mu_{\dot{A}},t_{1}\cdot\psi^{\alpha}\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then homogeneity demands
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
|a(\mathsf{W}'^{I})\rangle\,=\,t_{1}^{p}t_{2}^{q}\cdot|a(\mathsf{W}^{I})\rangle,\quad t_{1},t_{2}\in\mathbf{C}_{*}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a normed algebra,
 one may equip the space of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-valued functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 with the corresponding Fréchet topology.
 We then define the complex vector space
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{S}_{A}(p,q)\,\coloneqq\,\left\{ a:\mathbf{MT}_{s}\longrightarrow A\big|a\text{ is smooth and homogeneous of bi-degree }(p,q)\right\} .
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}_{A}(p,q)$
\end_inset

 admits the natural structure of a module over the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}^{\infty}(\mathbf{MT}_{s})$
\end_inset

 of complex-valued smooth functions on the minitwistor superspace.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathcal{S}_{A}(p,q)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in\mathscr{C}^{\infty}(\mathbf{MT}_{s})$
\end_inset

,
 we set:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(\varphi\cdot a)(\mathsf{W}^{I})\,\coloneqq\,\varphi\big(\pi_{0}(\mathsf{W}^{I})\big)\,|a(\mathsf{W}^{I})\rangle.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Main Result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our principal claim is that the module of smooth sections of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{A}(p,q)\stackrel{\pi}{\to}\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 coincides with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}_{A}(p,q)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\mathcal{O}_{A}(p,q)\big)\,\boldsymbol{\simeq}\,\mathcal{S}_{A}(p,q).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To prove the section/function correspondence,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\Gamma(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\mathcal{O}_{A}(p,q))$
\end_inset

 be a smooth section.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{W}^{I}\in\mathbf{M}$
\end_inset

 projecting to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{w}\in\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\circ s\circ\pi_{0}(\mathsf{W}^{I})=\mathsf{w}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\colon\mathbf{E}\longrightarrow\mathcal{O}_{A}(p,q)$
\end_inset

 is the quotient map,
 there exists a (unique) element 
\begin_inset Formula $|a(\mathsf{W}^{I})\rangle\in A$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q\big(\mathsf{W}^{I},|a(\mathsf{W}^{I})\rangle\big)=s\circ\pi_{0}(\mathsf{W}^{I}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Uniqueness follows because if also 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{a}:\mathsf{W}^{I}\mapsto|\tilde{a}(\mathsf{W}^{I})\rangle$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(\mathsf{W}^{I},\tilde{a})=s$
\end_inset

,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathsf{W}^{I},a)\equiv_{p,q}(\mathsf{W}^{I},\tilde{a})$
\end_inset

,
 which forces 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\tilde{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we obtain a well-defined map
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a\colon\mathbf{M}\longrightarrow A,\quad\mathsf{W}^{I}\mapsto|a(\mathsf{W}^{I})\rangle.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Smoothness of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 follows from that of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 together with the local triviality of the quotient.
 It remains to verify homogeneity.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{W}^{I}=(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 and for 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1},t_{2}\in\mathbf{C}_{*}$
\end_inset

 set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{W}'^{I}=(t_{1}\lambda^{A},t_{2}\mu_{\dot{A}},t_{1}\psi^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{0}(\mathsf{W}'^{I})=\pi_{0}(\mathsf{W}^{I})$
\end_inset

,
 the section takes the same value,
 
\begin_inset Formula $s(\pi_{0}(\mathsf{W}'^{I}))=s(\pi_{0}(\mathsf{W}^{I}))$
\end_inset

.
 Hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q(\mathsf{W}'^{I},|a(\mathsf{W}'^{I})\rangle)=Q(\mathsf{W}^{I},|a(\mathsf{W}^{I})\rangle).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By the defining equivalence on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}$
\end_inset

,
 this implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\big(\mathsf{W}'^{I},|a(\mathsf{W}'^{I})\rangle\big)\equiv_{p,q}\big(\mathsf{W}'^{I},t_{1}^{p}t_{2}^{q}\cdot|a(\mathsf{W}^{I})\rangle\big),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and uniqueness then yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
|a(\mathsf{W}'^{I})\rangle=t_{1}^{p}t_{2}^{q}\cdot|a(\mathsf{W}^{I})\rangle.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous of bi-degree 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,q)$
\end_inset

 and so belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}_{A}(p,q)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conversely,
 we construct a section from a homogeneous function 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathcal{S}_{A}(p,q)$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

-graded minitwistor point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{w}\in\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

,
 choose any coordinate representative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{W}^{I}\in\pi_{0}^{-1}(\mathsf{w})$
\end_inset

.
 We then define
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s(\mathsf{w})\coloneqq Q\big(\mathsf{W}^{I},|a(\mathsf{W}^{I})\rangle\big)\in\mathcal{O}_{A}(p,q).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To see that 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is well-defined,
 suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{W}'^{I}$
\end_inset

 is another lift of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{w}$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1},t_{2}\in\mathbf{C}_{*}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{W}'^{I}=(t_{1}\lambda^{A},t_{2}\mu_{\dot{A}},t_{1}\psi^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

.
 Homogeneity of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $|a(\mathsf{W}'^{I})\rangle=t_{1}^{p}t_{2}^{q}\cdot|a(\mathsf{W}^{I})\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q\big(\mathsf{W}'^{I},|a(\mathsf{W}'^{I})\rangle\big)=Q\big(\mathsf{W}'^{I},t_{1}^{p}t_{2}^{q}\cdot|a(\mathsf{W}^{I})\rangle\big)=Q\big(\mathsf{W}^{I},|a(\mathsf{W}^{I})\rangle\big),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $s(\mathsf{w})$
\end_inset

 is independent of the choice of representative.
 Smoothness of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 follows from that of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 together with the local triviality of the bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{A}(p,q)\stackrel{\pi}{\to}\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally,
 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a section because
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi\big(s(\mathsf{w})\big)=\pi\big(Q(\mathsf{W}^{I},|a(\mathsf{W}^{I})\rangle)\big)=Q_{0}\big(\mathsf{W}^{I},|a(\mathsf{W}^{I})\rangle\big)=\pi_{0}(\mathsf{W}^{I})=\mathsf{w},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\circ s=\text{id}_{\mathbf{MT}_{s}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\Gamma(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\mathcal{O}_{A}(p,q))$
\end_inset

,
 completing the correspondence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{A}^{*}(r,s)$
\end_inset

-bundle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A full understanding of minitwistor wavefunctions requires the introduction of the dual vector bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{A}^{*}(r,s)\stackrel{\pi^{*}}{\to}\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our correspondence between the holomorphic celestial supersphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{CS}$
\end_inset

 and the minitwistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 is mediated by the minitwistor transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{MT}$
\end_inset

.
 Unlike an ordinary Fourier transform,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{MT}$
\end_inset

 carries sections of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{A}(p,q)\stackrel{\pi}{\to}\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 to sections of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{A}^{*}(r,s)\stackrel{\pi^{*}}{\to}\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{A}^{*}(r,s)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous subsection,
 we fixed a normed algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 adapted to the background field theory or wavefunction in question.
 We now introduce its dual algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}$
\end_inset

,
 whose elements we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a|$
\end_inset

.
 We also define the auxiliary trivial bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}^{*}\coloneqq\mathbf{M}^{*}\times A^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the auxiliary bundle,
 we impose the equivalence:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\big(z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha},\langle a|\big)\cong_{r,s}\big(t_{1}\cdot z^{A},t_{2}\cdot\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},t_{1}^{-1}\cdot\eta^{\alpha},t_{1}^{r}t_{2}^{s}\cdot\langle a|\big),\quad\forall\,t_{1},t_{2}\in\mathbf{C}^{*}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The total space of the dual bundle is the quotient
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{O}_{A}^{*}(r,s)\,\coloneqq\,\mathbf{E}^{*}\boldsymbol{\big/}\cong_{r,s},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the natural projection 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{*}:\mathbf{E}^{*}\longrightarrow\mathcal{O}_{A}^{*}(r,s)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Dual Fibration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{pr}_{\mathbf{M}^{*}}:\mathbf{E}^{*}\longrightarrow\mathbf{M}^{*}$
\end_inset

 be the projection onto the first factor.
 Define
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{0}^{*}\colon\mathbf{E}^{*}\longrightarrow\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*},\quad Q_{0}^{*}\coloneqq\pi_{0}^{*}\circ\text{pr}_{\mathbf{M}^{*}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By construction,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{z}\in\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

 has any lift 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Z}^{I}\in(\pi_{0}^{*})^{-1}(\mathsf{z})$
\end_inset

,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}^{*}(\mathsf{Z}^{I},\langle a|)=\mathsf{z}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a|\in A^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 we define the dual fibration:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi^{*}:\mathcal{O}_{A}^{*}(r,s)\longrightarrow\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is uniquely specified by the requirement that the diagram
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation} 
\backslash
label{eq:comm-diagram-dual} 
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[   row sep=2cm,
   column sep=2cm,
   arrows={shorten <=4pt,
 shorten >=4pt},
   every label/.append style={font=} ]   & 
\backslash
mathbf{E}^{*}     
\backslash
arrow[dl,
 "Q^{*}"']     
\backslash
arrow[dr,
 "Q_{0}^{*}"]   & 
\backslash

\backslash
   
\backslash
mathcal{O}_{A}^{*}(r,s)     
\backslash
arrow[rr,
 "{
\backslash
pi^{*}}"{swap,yshift=-5pt}]   & & 
\backslash
mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*} 
\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{equation} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

commutes,
 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{*}\circ Q^{*}=Q_{0}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The description of sections of the dual bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{A}^{*}(r,s)$
\end_inset

 parallels that of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{A}(p,q)$
\end_inset

.
 A map
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a^{*}:\mathbf{M}^{*}\longrightarrow A^{*},\quad\mathsf{Z}^{I}\mapsto\langle a(\mathsf{Z}^{I})|
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is called an 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}$
\end_inset

-valued homogeneous function of bi-degree 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,s)$
\end_inset


\emph default
 if the following holds.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Z}^{I}=(z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 and,
 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1},t_{2}\in\mathbf{C}_{*}$
\end_inset

,
 set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Z}'^{I}=(t_{1}z^{A},t_{2}\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},t_{1}^{-1}\eta^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

.
 Then homogeneity demands:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle a(\mathsf{Z}'^{I})|=t_{1}^{r}t_{2}^{s}\cdot\langle a(\mathsf{Z}^{I})|.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To discuss the section/function correspondence on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{A}^{*}(r,s)\stackrel{\pi^{*}}{\to}\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

,
 define the dual function space:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{S}_{A}^{*}(r,s)\;\coloneqq\;\big\{\,a^{*}:\mathbf{M}^{*}\longrightarrow A^{*}\,\big|\,a^{*}\text{ smooth and homogeneous of bi-degree }(r,s)\big\}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here smoothness is understood in the Fréchet sense,
 since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}$
\end_inset

) carries a norm making it a Banach space.
 We therefore equip 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}_{A}^{*}(r,s)$
\end_inset

 with the induced Fréchet topology,
 rendering it a locally convex topological vector space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By exactly the same arguments as in the previous subsection,
 one shows that each 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}$
\end_inset

-valued homogeneous function 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{*}$
\end_inset

 defines a unique holomorphic section of the dual bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{A}^{*}(r,s)$
\end_inset

,
 and vice versa.
 Hence there is a natural isomorphism
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*};\mathcal{O}_{A}^{*}(r,s)\big)\,\boldsymbol{\simeq}\,\mathcal{S}_{A}^{*}(r,s).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Superforms and Currents on Minitwistor Superspace
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The projective delta function 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 appearing in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-39"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) indicates that the minitwistor superwavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}$
\end_inset

 is most naturally realised as a current
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The theory of currents was initiated by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "schwartz1954espaces,schwartz1957theorie,schwartz1958theorie"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "de2012differentiable"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A measure-theoretic framework was developed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "federer1965some,federer1959curvature,federer1960normal,federer2014geometric"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The complex-analytic aspects relevant to our discussion were reviewed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "king1971currents"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For a modern treatment emphasising positive line bundles in the context of algebraic geometry,
 see the review by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "demailly19962"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We now review the requisite differential-geometric framework.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Superforms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fix integers 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n,p,q\in\mathbf{Z}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq m,n\leq2$
\end_inset

.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigw^{m,n}\,\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 the exterior superbundle of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

-graded 
\begin_inset Formula $(m,n)$
\end_inset

-forms on minitwistor superspace.
 An element of this bundle is called an 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $(m,n)$
\end_inset

-superform
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider the sheaf of 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(p,q)$
\end_inset

-valued differential 
\begin_inset Formula $(m,n)$
\end_inset

-superforms
\emph default
.
 Explicitly,
 set
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Omega^{m,n}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(p,q)\big)\;\coloneqq\;\Gamma\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\bigw^{m,n}\,\mathbf{MT}_{s}\otimes\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(p,q)\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is a module over the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}^{\infty}(\mathbf{MT}_{s})$
\end_inset

.
 Equipped with the Whitney 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-topology
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We equip the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{m,n}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(p,q)\big)$
\end_inset

 with the following topology.
 A sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{\alpha}_{i})_{i\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(p,q)$
\end_inset

-valued differential 
\begin_inset Formula $(m,n)$
\end_inset

-superforms converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 if and only if,
 on each trivialising neighbourhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 of the bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(p,q)$
\end_inset

,
 the following holds:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Write 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{\alpha}_{i}-\boldsymbol{\alpha})_{i\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 in local coordinates as a finite collection of component functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every multi-index 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and every compact set 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subset U$
\end_inset

,
 the derivatives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D^{k}\boldsymbol{\alpha}_{i}-D^{k}\boldsymbol{\alpha}
\]

\end_inset

converge uniformly to zero on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $i\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In this way,
 all component functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{\alpha}_{i}-\boldsymbol{\alpha})_{i\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

,
 together with all their derivatives,
 vanish uniformly on compact subsets on each trivialising patch.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 this space becomes a locally convex,
 complete topological vector superspace over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Supercurrents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A supercurrent of bi-degree 
\begin_inset Formula $(2-m,2-n)$
\end_inset

 (equivalently bi-dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $(m,n)$
\end_inset

) over the bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(2-p,2-q)\stackrel{\pi}{\to}\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 is a continuous,
 complex-linear functional
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{T}\colon\Omega^{m,n}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(p-2,q-2)\big)\longrightarrow\mathbf{C}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Continuity is understood with respect to the Whitney 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-topology.
 The space of all such supercurrents is the strong-dual of the corresponding module of superforms:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathscr{D}'_{2-m,2-n}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(2-p,2-q)\big)\;\coloneqq\;\big(\Omega^{m,n}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(p-2,q-2)\big)\big)'.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

One extends the boundary and contraction operators from the exterior algebra of superforms to this space of currents.
 A natural wedge product exists between superforms and supercurrents.
 However,
 an exterior product of two supercurrents is not generically well defined.
 (See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Sec. 26"
key "simon1984lectures"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Minitwistor Superwavefunctions as Currents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the preceding framework in place,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}$
\end_inset

 is not an ordinary differential 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1)$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Instead,
 it defines a supercurrent of bi-degree 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1)$
\end_inset

 over the bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(\Delta-p,-\Delta)$
\end_inset

.
 To state this precisely,
 fix a dual 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

-graded minitwistor point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{z}\in\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and choose a coordinate representative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Z}^{I}\in(\pi_{0}^{*})^{-1}(\mathsf{z})$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{T}_{\Delta}^{p}\in\mathscr{D}'_{0,1}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(\Delta-p,-\Delta)\big),\quad\mathcal{T}_{\Delta}^{p}\;\coloneqq\;\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}(\;\cdot\;;\mathsf{Z}^{I}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Next,
 let
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\alpha}\in\Omega^{2,1}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(p-\Delta,\Delta)\big)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

be any differential 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,1)$
\end_inset

-superform with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(p-\Delta,\Delta)$
\end_inset

.
 By the section/function correspondence,
 there exists
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a\in\mathcal{S}_{\mathbf{C}}(p-\Delta+2,\Delta-2)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

such that on each trivialising neighbourhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 one has
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\alpha}\,\big|_{U}\;=\;a(\mathsf{W}^{I})\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence the action of the supercurrent 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\Delta}^{p}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle\mathcal{T}_{\Delta}^{p},\boldsymbol{\alpha}\rangle\;=\;\underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}\,\,\,}{\int}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}\,\,\,a(\mathsf{W}^{I})\wedge\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}(\mathsf{W}^{I};\mathsf{Z}^{I'}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the next subsection,
 we shall use this pairing to formulate the minitwistor transform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Currents on the Dual Superspace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We adopt the viewpoint that the minitwistor supergeometry is dual to the flat-space hologram on the holomorphic celestial supersphere.
 Consistency then demands that the minitwistor transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{MT}$
\end_inset

 be invertible.
 Equivalently,
 the family of superwavefunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\}$
\end_inset

 must also furnish a corresponding family of supercurrents on the 
\emph on
dual
\emph default
 minitwistor superspace.
 Accordingly,
 we extend the above discussion to currents valued in the bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}^{*}(p,q)\stackrel{\pi^{*}}{\to}\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Differential Superforms on Dual Space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigw^{m,n}\,\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

 be the exterior superbundle of complex 
\begin_inset Formula $(m,n)$
\end_inset

-superforms on the dual minitwistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 We consider the module of smooth sections
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Omega^{m,n}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*};\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}^{*}(p,q)\big)\;\coloneqq\;\Gamma\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*};\bigw^{m,n}\,\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}\otimes\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}^{*}(p,q)\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Endowed with the Whitney 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-topology,
 this becomes the locally convex,
 complete superspace of 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}^{*}(p,q)$
\end_inset

-valued differential 
\begin_inset Formula $(m,n)$
\end_inset

-superforms on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset


\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Dual Supercurrents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A supercurrent of bi-degree 
\begin_inset Formula $(2-m,2-n)$
\end_inset

 (equivalently bi-dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $(m,n)$
\end_inset

) over the bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}^{*}(2-p,2-q)\stackrel{\pi^{*}}{\to}\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is a continuous,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

-linear functional
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
^{*}\mathcal{T}\colon\Omega^{m,n}\big(\mathbf{MT}^{*};\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}^{*}(p-2,q-2)\big)\longrightarrow\mathbf{C}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Continuity is again with respect to the Whitney 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-topology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The space of supercurrents of bi-degree 
\begin_inset Formula $(2-m,2-n)$
\end_inset

 over the bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}^{*}(2-p,2-q)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathscr{D}'_{2-m,2-n}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*};\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}^{*}(2-p,2-q)\big)\;\coloneqq\;\big(\Omega^{m,n}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*};\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}^{*}(p-2,q-2)\big)\big)'
\end{equation}

\end_inset

endowed with the strong-dual topology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Supercurrents on the Dual Superspace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now associate to each minitwistor superwavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}$
\end_inset

 a supercurrent on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Fix a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

-graded minitwistor point 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathsf{W}^{I}]\in\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Then define
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
^{*}\mathcal{T}_{\Delta}^{p}\colon\mathscr{D}'_{0,1}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*};\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}^{*}(p-\Delta-2,-\Delta)\big),\quad^{*}\mathcal{T}_{\Delta}^{p}\;\coloneqq\;\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}(\mathsf{W}^{I};\;\cdot\;).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\beta}\in\Omega^{2,1}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*};\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}^{*}(\Delta-p+2,\Delta)\big)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

be any differential 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,1)$
\end_inset

-superform.
 By the section/function correspondence,
 there exists
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b\in\mathcal{S}_{\mathbf{C}}^{*}(\Delta-p-4,\Delta-2)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

such that on each trivialising neighbourhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{*}\subset\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\beta}\,\big|_{U^{*}}\;=\;b(\mathsf{W}^{I})\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence the action of the supercurrent on 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle^{*}\mathcal{T}_{\Delta}^{p},\boldsymbol{\beta}\rangle\;=\;\underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}}{\int}\,\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}(\mathsf{W}^{I};\mathsf{Z}^{I'})\wedge b(\mathsf{Z}^{I'})\;D^{2|4}\mathsf{Z}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the following subsection,
 this pairing will define the 
\emph on
inverse minitwistor transform
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{MT}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Minitwistor Transform
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now show that the family 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\}$
\end_inset

 of minitwistor wavefunctions is complete and orthogonal.
 Accordingly,
 we may interpret
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\big(\mathsf{Z}^{I};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big)
\]

\end_inset

as the wavefunction of an external gluon with conformal weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 and quantum numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This interpretation follows from the existence of a minitwistor transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{MT}$
\end_inset

.
 The mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{MT}$
\end_inset

 carries holomorphic sections on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 to those on its dual.
 Moreover,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{MT}$
\end_inset

 satisfies a Fourier-type inversion theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Completeness Relation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Completeness-Relation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To derive the completeness relation for the family 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\}$
\end_inset

,
 consider the differential form on the dual superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{a}\,\coloneqq\,a(z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha})\,\,\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{W},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a\big(z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big)\,\coloneqq\,\Psi_{\tilde{\Delta}}^{\tilde{p}}\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big)\widetilde{\Psi}_{\Delta}^{p}\big(\sigma^{A},\omega_{\dot{A}},\chi^{\alpha};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The integral
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}\,\,\,}{\int}\,\,\,\boldsymbol{a}
\]

\end_inset

exists when 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 is invariant under the transformation of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-31"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-30"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-38"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 defines a volume form when:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta+\tilde{\Delta}=2,\qquad p+\tilde{p}=0.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We therefore set:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{a}\,=\,\Psi_{2-\Delta}^{-p}\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big)\,\widetilde{\Psi}_{\Delta}^{p}\big(\sigma^{A},\omega_{\dot{A}},\chi^{\alpha};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big)\,\,\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Substituting the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}$
\end_inset

 from Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-39"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{a}\,=\,\overline{\delta}_{p-\Delta}\left(z,\sigma\right)\overline{\delta}_{\Delta-p-2}(z,\lambda)\frac{\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)\mathcal{C}\left(2-\Delta\right)}{[\bar{z}\omega]^{\Delta}[\mu\bar{z}]^{2-\Delta}}\exp\left(i\frac{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }\left(\psi-\frac{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle \sigma\iota\right\rangle }\chi\right)\cdot\eta\right)\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Finally,
 integrating over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

 yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}\,\,\,}{\int}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}\,\,\,\Psi_{2-\Delta}^{-p}\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big)\,\widetilde{\Psi}_{\Delta}^{p}\big(\sigma^{A},\omega_{\dot{A}},\chi^{\alpha};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big)\\
 & \,\,\,=\,\,\,\overline{\delta}_{p-\Delta}\left(\lambda,\sigma\right)\,\delta^{0|4}\left(\psi-\frac{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle \sigma\iota\right\rangle }\chi\right)\,\underset{\mathbf{CP}^{1}\,\,\,\,\,}{\int}\,D\bar{z}\,\,\,\frac{\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)\mathcal{C}\left(2-\Delta\right)}{[\bar{z}\omega]^{\Delta}[\mu\bar{z}]^{2-\Delta}}.\label{eq:-33}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We proceed by considering the integral:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{I}\big(\mu_{\dot{A}},\omega_{\dot{B}}\big)\,\coloneqq\,\underset{\mathbf{CP}^{1}\,\,\,\,\,}{\int}\,D\bar{z}\,\,\,\frac{\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)\mathcal{C}\left(2-\Delta\right)}{[\bar{z}\omega]^{\Delta}[\mu\bar{z}]^{2-\Delta}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This expression is well-defined only in a distributional sense.
 Indeed,
 if one assumes that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 admits an analytic form,
 then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{I}\big(t_{1}\cdot\mu_{\dot{A}},t_{2}\cdot\omega_{\dot{B}}\big)\,=\,t_{1}^{\Delta-2}\,t_{2}^{-\Delta}\,\mathcal{I}\big(\mu_{\dot{A}},\omega_{\dot{B}}\big),\qquad\forall\,t_{1},t_{2}\in\mathbf{C}^{*}.\label{eq:-32}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Lorentz invariance,
 by contrast,
 requires 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 to scale as a power of 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mu\omega]$
\end_inset

.
 These two requirements are incompatible unless the proportionality factors vanishes or diverges.
 This is precisely the behaviour of the projective delta function 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sharma2022ambidextrous"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 this is confirmed by explicit integration:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\mathbf{CP}^{1}\,\,\,\,\,}{\int}\,D\bar{z}\,\,\,\frac{\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)\mathcal{C}\left(2-\Delta\right)}{[\bar{z}\omega]^{\Delta}[\mu\bar{z}]^{2-\Delta}}\,=\,4\pi^{2}\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}\left(\mu,\omega\right).\label{eq:-43}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Substitution into Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-33"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) then yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}\,\,\,}{\int}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}\,\,\,\Psi_{2-\Delta}^{-p}\left(\lambda,\mu,\psi;z,\bar{z},\eta\right)\,\widetilde{\Psi}_{\Delta}^{p}\left(\sigma,\omega,\chi;z,\bar{z},\eta\right)\label{eq:-36}\\
 & \,\,\,=\,\,\,4\pi^{2}\,\overline{\delta}_{p-\Delta}\left(\lambda,\sigma\right)\,\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}\left(\mu,\omega\right)\,\delta^{0|4}\left(\psi^{\alpha}-\frac{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle \sigma\iota\right\rangle }\chi^{\alpha}\right).
\end{align}

\end_inset

This establishes the completeness relation for minitwistor wavefunctions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Minitwistor Delta Function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-36"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) is rather involved.
 We seek a concise reformulation that makes its homogeneity properties manifest.
 To this end,
 we extend the projective delta function 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 to the minitwistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 This extension should preserve covariance under the transformation law of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-1"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the 
\emph on
minitwistor delta function
\emph default
 with homogeneities 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{1},\Delta_{2}$
\end_inset

 by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}_{\Delta_{1},\Delta_{2}}^{2|4}\big(\mathsf{Z}^{I};\mathsf{Z}'^{J}\big)\,=\,\underset{\mathbf{C}^{*}\,\,\,}{\int}\,\frac{dt_{1}}{t_{1}}\,t_{1}^{\Delta_{1}}\,\underset{\mathbf{C}^{*}\,\,\,}{\int}\,\frac{dt_{2}}{t_{2}}\,t_{2}^{\Delta_{2}}\,\,\,\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(\lambda^{A}-t_{1}\sigma^{A}\big)\,\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(\mu_{\dot{A}}-t_{2}\omega_{\dot{A}}\big)\,\delta^{0|4}\big(\psi^{\alpha}-t_{1}\chi^{\alpha}\big),\label{eq:-34}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathsf{Z}^{I}\,\coloneqq\,\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha}\big),\,\,\,\mathsf{Z}'^{I}\,\coloneqq\,\big(\sigma^{A},\omega_{\dot{A}},\chi^{\alpha}\big)\in\mathbf{MT}_{s}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota^{A}$
\end_inset

 be an auxiliary non-vanishing spinor.
 Using the fundamental solution of the Dolbeault operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\partial}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

,
 we find:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(\lambda^{A}-t_{1}\sigma^{A}\big)\,=\,\frac{1}{\left(2\pi i\right)^{2}}\,\bigwedge_{A\in\{1,2\}}\,\overline{\partial}\,\,\,\frac{1}{\lambda^{A}-t_{1}\sigma^{A}}\,=\,\overline{\delta}\left(t_{1}-\frac{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle \sigma\iota\right\rangle }\right)\overline{\delta}\left(\left\langle \sigma\lambda\right\rangle \right),\label{eq:-45}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(\mu_{\dot{A}}-t_{2}\omega_{\dot{A}}\big)\,=\,\frac{1}{\left(2\pi i\right)^{2}}\,\bigwedge_{\dot{A}\in\{\dot{1},\dot{2}\}}\,\overline{\partial}\,\,\,\frac{1}{\mu_{\dot{A}}-t_{2}\omega_{\dot{A}}}\,=\,\overline{\delta}\left(t_{2}-\frac{[\mu\bar{\iota}]}{[\omega\bar{\iota}]}\right)\overline{\delta}\left([\omega\mu]\right).\label{eq:-46}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By substituting into Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-34"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and invoking the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 from Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-35"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}_{\Delta_{1},\Delta_{2}}^{2|4}\big(\mathsf{Z};\mathsf{Z}'\big)\,=\,\overline{\delta}_{\Delta_{1}}\big(\lambda^{A},\sigma^{A}\big)\,\overline{\delta}_{\Delta_{2}}\big(\mu_{\dot{A}},\omega_{\dot{A}}\big)\,\delta^{0|4}\left(\psi^{\alpha}-\frac{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle \sigma\iota\right\rangle }\chi^{\alpha}\right).\label{eq:-179}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Canonical Form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the minitwistor delta function,
 the completeness relation in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-36"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) can be written as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}\,\,\,}{\int}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}\,\,\,\Psi_{2-\Delta}^{-p}\left(\mathsf{Z};\mathsf{W}\right)\,\widetilde{\Psi}_{\Delta}^{p}\left(\mathsf{Z}';\mathsf{W}\right)\,=\,4\pi^{2}\,\overline{\delta}_{p-\Delta,\Delta}^{2|4}\left(\mathsf{Z};\mathsf{Z}'\right).\label{eq:-37}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We now adopt a simple convention for the conjugate wavefunction.
 Define:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\left(\mathsf{W};\mathsf{Z}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\widetilde{\Psi}_{\Delta}^{p}\left(\mathsf{Z};\mathsf{W}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

With this definition,
 Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-37"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) takes the canonical form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}\,\,\,}{\int}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}\,\,\,\Psi_{2-\Delta}^{-p}\left(\mathsf{Z};\mathsf{W}\right)\,\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\left(\mathsf{W};\mathsf{Z}'\right)\,=\,4\pi^{2}\,\overline{\delta}_{p-\Delta,\Delta}^{2|4}\left(\mathsf{Z};\mathsf{Z}'\right).\label{eq:-40}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Orthogonality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To prove that the minitwistor transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{MT}$
\end_inset

 is invertible,
 we derive an orthogonality relation for the family 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\}$
\end_inset

 of minitwistor wavefunctions.
 Whereas completeness (Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-40"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

)) follows from integrating a differential form over the dual superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

,
 orthogonality is obtained by integrating over the superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First,
 define the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

-graded differential form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{b}\,\coloneqq\,b\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha}\big)\,\,\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{Z},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha}\big)\,\coloneqq\,\widetilde{\Psi}_{\tilde{\Delta}}^{\tilde{p}}\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big)\,\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha};z'^{A},\bar{z}'_{\dot{A}},\eta'^{\alpha}\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The integral
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}\,\,\,}{\int}\,\,\,\boldsymbol{b}
\]

\end_inset

is well-defined only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}$
\end_inset

 is invariant under the transformations of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-1"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-29"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}$
\end_inset

 is a volume form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 when:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta+\tilde{\Delta}=2,\qquad p+\tilde{p}=0.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Accordingly,
 we set:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{b}\,=\,\widetilde{\Psi}_{2-\Delta}^{-p}\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big)\,\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha};z'^{A},\bar{z}'_{\dot{A}},\eta'^{\alpha}\big)\,\,\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{Z}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Next,
 substitute the explicit forms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\Psi}_{\Delta}^{p}$
\end_inset

 from Eqs.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-39"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-41"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 One obtains:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{b}\,=\,\overline{\delta}_{p-\Delta}\left(z',\lambda\right)\,\overline{\delta}_{\Delta-p-2}\left(z,\lambda\right)\,\frac{\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)\mathcal{C}\left(2-\Delta\right)}{[\mu\bar{z}']^{\Delta}[\bar{z}\mu]^{2-\Delta}}\,\exp\left(-i\frac{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }\psi\cdot\left(\eta-\frac{\left\langle z'\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }\eta'\right)\right)\,\,\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{Z}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We then integrate over the minitwistor superspace:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}\,\,\,}{\int}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{Z}\,\,\,\widetilde{\Psi}_{2-\Delta}^{-p}\left(\lambda,\mu,\psi;z,\bar{z},\eta\right)\,\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\left(\lambda,\mu,\psi;z',\bar{z}',\eta'\right)\\
 & \,=\,\left(\frac{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle z'\iota\right\rangle }\right)^{4}\,\overline{\delta}_{\Delta-p-2}\left(z,z'\right)\,\delta^{0|4}\left(\eta^{\alpha}-\frac{\left\langle z'\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }\eta'^{\alpha}\right)\,\underset{\mathbf{CP}^{1}\,\,\,}{\int}\,D\mu\,\,\,\frac{\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)\mathcal{C}\left(2-\Delta\right)}{[\mu\bar{z}']^{\Delta}[\bar{z}\mu]^{2-\Delta}}.\label{eq:-42}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Using Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-35"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) for the projective delta function on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

,
 we have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}_{\Delta-p+2}\left(z,z'\right)\,=\,\overline{\delta}\left(\left\langle z'z\right\rangle \right)\,\left(\frac{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle z'\iota\right\rangle }\right)^{\left(\Delta-p+2\right)-1}\,=\,\left(\frac{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle z'\iota\right\rangle }\right)^{4}\,\overline{\delta}_{\Delta-p-2}\left(z,z'\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Substituting into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-42"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and using the integral identity of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-43"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) gives the final result:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}\,\,\,}{\int}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{Z}\,\,\,\widetilde{\Psi}_{2-\Delta}^{-p}\left(\lambda,\mu,\psi;z,\bar{z},\eta\right)\,\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\left(\lambda,\mu,\psi;z',\bar{z}',\eta'\right)\\
 & \,=\,4\pi^{2}\,\overline{\delta}_{\Delta-p+2}\left(z,z'\right)\,\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}\left(\bar{z},\bar{z}'\right)\,\delta^{0|4}\left(\eta^{\alpha}-\frac{\left\langle z'\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }\eta'^{\alpha}\right).\label{eq:-44}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Dual Delta Function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-44"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) is impractical for explicit calculations.
 To remedy this,
 we extend the projective delta function 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 to a dual-minitwistor delta function on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 This new distribution must transform homogeneously under rescalings,
 in accordance with Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-31"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the 
\emph on
dual-minitwistor delta function
\emph default
 with homogeneity degrees 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{2}$
\end_inset

 by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{\delta}_{\Delta_{1},\Delta_{2}}^{2|4}\left(\mathsf{W}^{I},\mathsf{W}'^{J}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\underset{\mathbf{C}^{*}\,\,\,}{\int}\,\frac{dt_{1}}{t_{1}}\,t_{1}^{\Delta_{1}}\,\underset{\mathbf{C}^{*}\,\,\,}{\int}\,\frac{dt_{2}}{t_{2}}\,t_{2}^{\Delta_{2}}\,\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(z^{A}-t_{1}z'^{A}\big)\,\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(\bar{z}_{\dot{A}}-t_{2}\bar{z}'_{\dot{A}}\big)\delta^{0|4}\left(\eta^{\alpha}-t_{1}^{-1}\eta'^{\alpha}\right),\label{eq:-47}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathsf{W}^{I}\,\coloneqq\,\big(z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big),\,\,\,\mathsf{W}'^{I}\,\coloneqq\,\big(z'^{A},\bar{z}'_{\dot{A}},\eta'^{\alpha}\big)\in\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}.
\]

\end_inset

Substituting Eqs.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-45"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-46"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) into Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-47"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{\delta}_{\Delta_{1},\Delta_{2}}^{2|4}\left(\mathsf{W};\mathsf{W}'\right)\,=\,\overline{\delta}_{\Delta_{1}}\left(z,z'\right)\,\overline{\delta}_{\Delta_{2}}\left(\bar{z},\bar{z}'\right)\,\delta^{0|4}\left(\eta^{\alpha}-\frac{\left\langle z'\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }\eta'^{\alpha}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Finally,
 using the convention:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi_{2-\Delta}^{-p}\left(\mathsf{W};\mathsf{Z}\right)\,=\,\widetilde{\Psi}_{2-\Delta}^{-p}\left(\mathsf{Z};\mathsf{W}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

the orthogonality relation becomes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}\,\,\,}{\int}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{Z}\,\,\,\Psi_{2-\Delta}^{-p}\left(\mathsf{W};\mathsf{Z}\right)\,\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\left(\mathsf{Z};\mathsf{W}'\right)\,=\,4\pi^{2}\,\widetilde{\delta}_{\Delta-p+2,\Delta}^{2|4}\left(\mathsf{W};\mathsf{W}'\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Minitwistor Fourier Transform
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Minitwistor-Fourier-Transform"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having established the completeness and orthogonality of the family 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\}$
\end_inset

,
 we now introduce the minitwistor transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{MT}$
\end_inset

 and its inverse.
 Unlike the ordinary Fourier transform,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{MT}$
\end_inset

 sends sections of holomorphic vector bundles over the minitwistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 to sections over the dual superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Preliminaries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varphi\coloneqq\varphi\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha}\big)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

be a holomorphic section of the bundle
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{O}\left(w_{1}\right)\oplus\mathcal{O}\left(w_{2}\right)\longrightarrow\mathbf{MT}_{s}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Define the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

-graded differential form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{c}\,\coloneqq\,\varphi\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big)\,\widetilde{\Psi}_{\Delta}^{p}\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big)\,\,\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{Z}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For the integral
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}\,\,\,}{\int}\,\,\,\boldsymbol{c}
\]

\end_inset

to be well-defined,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}$
\end_inset

 must be invariant under the rescalings of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-1"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-29"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-44"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}$
\end_inset

 is a volume form precisely when:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w_{1}=p-\Delta+2,\qquad w_{2}=\Delta-2.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence we take
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:E\longrightarrow B$
\end_inset

 be a holomorphic vector superbundle over the base 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(E;B)$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(B)$
\end_inset

-module of holomorphic sections of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varphi\in\Gamma\big(\mathcal{O}(p-\Delta+2)\oplus\mathcal{O}(\Delta-2);\mathbf{MT}_{s}\big).\label{eq:-49}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define the 
\emph on
minitwistor transform
\emph default
 of a section 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 :
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Phi\left(\mathsf{W}^{I}\right)\coloneqq\mathcal{MT}\big[\varphi(\mathsf{Z}^{J})\big](\mathsf{W}^{I}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Phi\left(z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}\,\,\,}{\int}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{Z}\,\,\,\varphi\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\right)\,\widetilde{\Psi}_{\Delta}^{p}\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big).\label{eq:-48}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

From the homogeneity laws in Eqs.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-30"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-31"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 one finds:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Phi\big(t_{1}\cdot z^{A},t_{2}\cdot\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},t_{1}^{-1}\cdot\eta^{\alpha}\big)\,=\,t_{1}^{p-\Delta-2}\,t_{2}^{-\Delta}\,\Phi\big(z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big),\qquad\forall\,t_{1},t_{2}\in\mathbf{C}^{*}.\label{eq:-155}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 is a section of:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{O}\left(p-\Delta-2\right)\oplus\mathcal{O}\left(-\Delta\right)\longrightarrow\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Accordingly,
 the transform acts as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{MT}:\Gamma\big(\mathcal{O}(p-\Delta+2)\oplus\mathcal{O}(\Delta-2);\mathbf{MT}_{s}\big)\longrightarrow\Gamma\big(\mathcal{O}\left(p-\Delta-2\right)\oplus\mathcal{O}\left(-\Delta\right);\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Inversion Theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now derive the inversion of the minitwistor transform using the completeness relation of Subsec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Completeness-Relation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and Fubini's theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the superform on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{d}\,\coloneqq\,\Psi_{\tilde{\Delta}}^{\tilde{p}}\big(\lambda'^{A},\mu'_{\dot{A}},\psi'^{\alpha};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big)\,\Phi\big(z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big)\,\,\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-29"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-155"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}$
\end_inset

 is a volume form when:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{p}=-p,\qquad\tilde{\Delta}=2-\Delta.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Accordingly,
 we define the 
\emph on
inverse transform 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{MT}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{MT}^{-1}[\Phi]\big(\lambda'^{A},\mu'_{\dot{A}},\psi'^{\alpha}\big)\,\coloneqq\,\frac{1}{4\pi^{2}}\underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}\,\,\,}{\int}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}\,\,\,\Psi_{2-\Delta}^{-p}\big(\lambda'^{A},\mu'_{\dot{A}},\psi'^{\alpha}|z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big)\,\Phi\big(z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big).\label{eq:-51}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 from Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-48"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and apply Fubini's theorem.
 One finds:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \mathcal{MT}^{-1}[\Phi]\left(\lambda',\mu',\psi'\right)\,=\,\frac{1}{4\pi^{2}}\,\underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}\,\,\,}{\int}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{Z}\,\,\,\varphi\left(\lambda,\mu,\eta\right)\,\,\,\\
 & \underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}\,\,\,}{\int}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}\,\,\,\Psi_{2-\Delta}^{-p}\left(\lambda',\mu',\psi';z,\bar{z},\eta\right)\,\widetilde{\Psi}_{\Delta}^{p}\left(\lambda,\mu,\eta;z,\bar{z},\eta\right).
\end{align}

\end_inset

Invoking the completeness relation (Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-40"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

)) yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{MT}^{-1}[\Phi]\left(\lambda',\mu',\psi'\right)\,=\,\varphi\left(\lambda',\mu',\psi'\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence the inversion formula is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varphi\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big)\,=\,\frac{1}{4\pi^{2}}\,\underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}\,\,\,}{\int}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}\,\,\,\Psi_{2-\Delta}^{-p}\left(\lambda,\mu,\psi;z,\bar{z},\eta\right)\,\Phi\left(z,\bar{z},\eta\right).\label{eq:-50}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 if one takes this as the defining relation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 given 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 and applies orthogonality,
 then Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-51"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) follows from Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-50"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 We summarise our results below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Summary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathsf{Z}^{I}\,\coloneqq\,\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha}\big),\qquad\mathsf{W}^{I'}\,\coloneqq\,\big(z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha}\big)
\]

\end_inset

parametrise the minitwistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 and its dual 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

,
 respectively.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{2|4}\mathsf{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}$
\end_inset

 the corresponding measures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi\,\in\,\Gamma\big(\mathcal{O}\left(p-\Delta+2\right)\oplus\mathcal{O}\left(\Delta-2\right);\mathbf{MT}_{s}\big)
\]

\end_inset

and let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Phi\,\in\,\Gamma\big(\mathcal{O}\left(p-\Delta-2\right)\oplus\mathcal{O}\left(-\Delta\right);\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}\big).
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 are related by the integral transform:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Phi\left(\mathsf{W}\right)\,=\,\mathcal{MT}\big[\varphi\left(\mathsf{Z}\right)\big]\left(\mathsf{W}\right)\,=\,\underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}\,\,\,}{\int}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{Z}\,\,\,\varphi\left(\mathsf{Z}\right)\,\widetilde{\Psi}_{\Delta}^{p}\left(\mathsf{Z};\mathsf{W}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

if and only if its inverse holds:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varphi\left(\mathsf{Z}\right)\,=\,\mathcal{MT}^{-1}\big[\Phi\left(\mathsf{W}\right)\big]\left(\mathsf{Z}\right)\,=\,\underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}\,\,\,}{\int}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}\,\,\,\Psi_{2-\Delta}^{-p}\left(\mathsf{Z};\mathsf{W}\right)\,\Phi\left(\mathsf{W}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Celestial BMSW Identity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the principal results of this work is the geometric and dynamical reformulations of the celestial leaf amplitudes for gluons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the geometric formulation,
 we will express the celestial amplitudes as expectation values of holomorphic Wilson loops on minitwistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 These Wilson loops are supported on a family of nodal minitwistor lines.
 Expanding the path-ordered exponential that defines the holonomy of the pseudoholomorphic connection will produce the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-fold Penrose transform of the minitwistor superwavefunctions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the dynamical formulation,
 we will realise the celestial amplitudes as semiclassical expectation values of correlators in the minitwistor sigma-model.
 These correlators will be encoded by the Quillen determinant of a gauge potential on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Their evaluation again reduces to an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-fold Penrose transform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A key ingredient in both reformulations is the supersymmetric generalisation of the celestial Boels-Mason-Skinner-Witten (BMSW) identity.
 The bosonic version was derived in Mol (2025).
 This identity states that the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-fold Penrose transform of the minitwistor superwavefunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}$
\end_inset

 coincides with the integral kernel of the Mellin-transformed Parke-Taylor factors appearing in the gluon amplitudes.
 We shall now present its derivation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Preliminaries
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Preliminaries"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The central result of this subsection rests on the minitwistor Penrose transform
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "jones1984minitwistors,jones1985minitwistor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We therefore recall the geometric structures on which it is defined.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The supersymmetric extension of the Hitchin correspondence
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hitchin1982monopoles,hitchin1982twistor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 establishes a bijection between points of the minitwistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 and totally geodesic null hypersurfaces in an Einstein-Weyl supermanifold
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "leites2002einstein,dewitt1992supermanifolds,rogers2007supermanifolds,leites1980introduction,manin1997introduction"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely,
 each point of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a distinguished curve in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

,
 known as a 
\emph on
minitwistor line
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our case,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 supersymmetric extension of an open subset of the quadric 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}\times\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 One finds that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

 is then the complexification of the 
\begin_inset Formula $(3|8)$
\end_inset

-dimensional anti-de Sitter superspace
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "koning2025anti"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The precise interplay among 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

 and the projective spinor superbundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}(\mathcal{S})$
\end_inset

 will emerge in our definition of the double fibration below.
 Before that,
 however,
 we review the projective model for the hyperbolic supergeometry of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Projective Model of Hyperbolic Space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We give a concise construction of the three-dimensional hyperbolic model in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 For the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional case,
 see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bailey1998twistor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 be homogeneous coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 In abstract index notation,
 the statement 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A\dot{A}}\in\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

 is to be interpreted as the equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $[X_{A\dot{A}}]$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the bilinear form and its associated norm by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(X,Y)\;\coloneqq\;\varepsilon_{\overset{}{A}\overset{}{B}}\varepsilon_{\dot{A}\dot{B}}X^{A\dot{A}}Y^{B\dot{B}},\quad\left\Vert X\right\Vert ^{2}\;\coloneqq\;-(X,X),\quad\forall\,X_{A\dot{A}},Y_{A\dot{A}}\in\mathbf{CP}^{3}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}$
\end_inset

 denote the complexified null cone,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathscr{C}\;\coloneqq\;\big\{\,X_{A\dot{A}}\in\mathbf{CP}^{3}\,\big|\,\Vert X\Vert=0\,\big\}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The complex hyperbolic space is then the open submanifold 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}\coloneqq\mathbf{CP}^{3}\backslash\mathscr{C}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define a metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{g}_{A\dot{A}B\dot{B}}$
\end_inset

 on the hyperbolic space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}$
\end_inset

 by requiring that its line element in the dual coordinate basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{dX^{A\dot{A}}\}$
\end_inset

 takes the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
ds^{2}\;\coloneqq\;\boldsymbol{g}_{A\dot{A}B\dot{B}}\,dX^{A\dot{A}}dX^{B\dot{B}}\;=\;-\frac{1}{\Vert X\Vert^{2}}\,\left(\Vert dX\Vert^{2}-\frac{(X,dX)^{2}}{\Vert X\Vert^{2}}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By construction,
 this metric is invariant under overall rescaling of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

,
 and has no component along the radial (scale) direction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To formalise these properties,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\coloneqq X^{A\dot{A}}\nabla_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 be the Euler vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

,
 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla_{A\dot{A}}\;\coloneqq\;\frac{\partial}{\partial X^{A\dot{A}}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The metric then satisfies:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathscr{L}_{\xi}\;\boldsymbol{g}_{A\dot{A}B\dot{B}}\;=\;0,\quad\xi^{A\dot{A}}\boldsymbol{g}_{A\dot{A}B\dot{B}}\;=\;0,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{L}_{\xi}$
\end_inset

 denotes the Lie derivative along 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The natural orientation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}$
\end_inset

 is specified by the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(4)$
\end_inset

-valued differential 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D^{3}X\;\coloneqq\;\varepsilon_{[\overset{}{A}\overset{}{B}}\varepsilon_{\overset{}{C}\overset{}{D}]}\varepsilon_{[\dot{A}\dot{B}}\varepsilon_{\dot{C}\dot{D}]}\;X^{A\dot{A}}\,dX^{B\dot{B}}\wedge dX^{C\dot{C}}\wedge dX^{D\dot{D}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assert that the triple 
\begin_inset Formula $\big(\mathbf{H},\mathbf{g}_{A\dot{A}B\dot{B}},D^{3}X\big)$
\end_inset

 realises three-dimensional hyperbolic space.
 To see this,
 define the weightless coordinate function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{R}_{A\dot{A}}:\mathbf{H}\longrightarrow\mathbf{C}^{4},\quad\mathcal{R}_{A\dot{A}}\coloneqq\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\Vert X\Vert}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

A direct computation shows
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
ds^{2}\;=\;\varepsilon_{\overset{}{A}\overset{}{B}}\varepsilon_{\dot{A}\dot{B}}\,d\mathcal{R}^{A\dot{A}}d\mathcal{R}^{B\dot{B}}\quad\text{and}\quad\Vert\mathcal{R}\Vert^{2}\coloneqq-\mathcal{R}_{A\dot{A}}\mathcal{R}^{A\dot{A}}=1.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus the map 
\begin_inset Formula $e\colon X_{A\dot{A}}\mapsto\mathcal{R}_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 embeds 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}$
\end_inset

 isometrically onto the hyperboloid:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{3}\;\coloneqq\;\big\{\,\mathcal{R}_{A\dot{A}}\in\mathbf{C}^{4}\,\big|\,\Vert\mathcal{R}\Vert^{2}=1\big\},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

the standard model of three-dimensional hyperbolic space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 one checks that the pullback (via 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{*}$
\end_inset

) of the standard volume form on 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}$
\end_inset

 lies in the same orientation class as 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{3}X$
\end_inset

.
 This completes the identification of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}$
\end_inset

 with the classical hyperbolic geometry of 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To formulate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM theory,
 we must employ the supersymmetric Hitchin correspondence.
 In the forthcoming discussion of the double fibration on the projective spinor bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}(\mathcal{S})$
\end_inset

,
 we will introduce the minitwistor incidence relations.
 These relations identify the 
\emph on
minitwistor lines
\emph default
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 as distinguished curves.
 It then follows that 
\emph on
the moduli space of these lines in the 
\begin_inset Formula $(2|4)$
\end_inset

-dimensional minitwistor superspace is diffeomorphic to the 
\begin_inset Formula $(3|8)$
\end_inset

-dimensional hyperbolic superspace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Hyperbolic Superspace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before presenting the supersymmetric Hitchin correspondence in detail,
 we extend our hyperbolic model 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}$
\end_inset

 by adjoining fermionic directions.
 The appropriate mathematical framework is that of a vector superbundle,
 as discussed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "manin1997introduction"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "rogers2007supermanifolds"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define the
\emph on
 
\begin_inset Formula $(3|8)$
\end_inset

-dimensional hyperbolic superspace
\emph default
 as the trivial vector superbundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}\coloneqq\mathbf{H}\times\mathbf{C}^{0|8}$
\end_inset

.
 Its fibre is the vector superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}^{0|8}$
\end_inset

 spanned by the Grassmann-valued van der Waerden spinors 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{A}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 Each fibre carries the orientation provided by Berezin's measure 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{0|8}\theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A global trivialisation is provided by the superchart
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathsf{X}^{K}\colon\mathbf{H}_{s}\longrightarrow\mathbf{CP}^{3}\times\mathbf{C}^{0|8},\quad\mathsf{X}^{K}\;\coloneqq\;\big(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\big),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 indexes both bosonic and fermionic dimensions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The canonical orientation measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D^{3|8}\mathsf{X}\;\coloneqq\;\frac{D^{3}X}{\Vert X\Vert^{4}}\wedge d^{0|8}\theta.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

 as a trivial superbundle,
 we have imposed projective invariance solely along the bosonic (horizontal) directions.
 Therefore,
 under the scale transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\mapsto t\cdot X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{3|8}\mathsf{X}$
\end_inset

 remains invariant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Double Fibration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Penrose transform is most naturally formulated via a double fibration.
 We now define the fibration that realises the supersymmetric Hitchin correspondence for the minitwistor superspace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}(\mathcal{S})\coloneqq\mathbf{CP}^{3|8}\times\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 be the complex projective spinor superbundle over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{3|8}\coloneqq\mathbf{CP}^{3}\times\mathbf{C}^{0|8}$
\end_inset

.
 Define the open submanifold
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{P}'(\mathcal{S})\;\coloneqq\;\big\{\,\big(\mathsf{X}^{K},[\lambda^{A}]\big)\in\mathbf{P}(\mathcal{S})\,\big|\,\Vert X\Vert\neq0\,\big\}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We have two projections from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}'(\mathcal{S})$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau\colon\mathbf{P}'(\mathcal{S})\longrightarrow\mathbf{H}_{s},\quad\tau\big(\mathsf{X}^{K},[\lambda^{A}]\big)\coloneqq\big(\mathsf{X}^{K}\big),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\upsilon\colon\mathbf{P}'(\mathcal{S})\longrightarrow\mathbf{MT}_{s}\quad\upsilon\big(\mathsf{X}^{K},[\lambda^{A}]\big)\coloneqq\pi_{0}\big(\lambda^{A},\lambda^{A}X_{A\dot{A}},\lambda^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The product map
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau\times\upsilon\colon\mathbf{P}'(\mathcal{S})\longrightarrow\mathbf{H}_{s}\times\mathbf{MT}_{s}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is an embedding,
 and we denote its image by 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathbf{P}'(\mathcal{S})}\subset\mathbf{H}_{s}\times\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fix a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{X}^{K}\in\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Its 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

-fibre is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}_{\mathsf{X}^{K}}\coloneqq\tau^{-1}(\mathsf{X}^{K})$
\end_inset

.
 Under the embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\times\upsilon$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}_{\mathsf{X}^{K}}$
\end_inset

 maps to a submanifold of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we obtain a family 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathscr{F}_{\mathsf{X}^{K}}\}_{\mathsf{X}^{K}\in\mathbf{H}_{s}}$
\end_inset

 of submanifolds in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 parametrised by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}_{\mathsf{X}^{K}}$
\end_inset

 is precisely the 
\emph on
minitwistor line
\emph default
 corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{X}^{K}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly,
 fix a minitwistor point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{w}\in\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Its 
\begin_inset Formula $\upsilon$
\end_inset

-fibre is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{G}_{\mathsf{w}}\coloneqq\upsilon^{-1}(\mathsf{w})$
\end_inset

.
 Under 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\times\upsilon$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{G}_{\mathsf{w}}$
\end_inset

 embeds as a submanifold of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence there is a family 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathscr{G}_{\mathsf{w}}\}_{\mathsf{w}\in\mathbf{MT}_{s}}$
\end_inset

 of submanifolds in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

 parametrised by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 In Hitchin's correspondence,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{G}_{\mathsf{w}}$
\end_inset

 is the totally geodesic null hypersurface associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{w}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore,
 the correspondence is summarised by the double fibration:
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{eq:comm-diagram-tau-upsilon-small} 
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[row sep=1.732cm,
 column sep=2cm,
 arrows={shorten <=4pt,
 shorten >=4pt}]   & 
\backslash
mathbf{P}'(
\backslash
mathcal{S})     
\backslash
arrow[dl,
 "
\backslash
tau"']     
\backslash
arrow[dr,
 "
\backslash
upsilon"]   & 
\backslash

\backslash
   
\backslash
mathbf{H}_{s}   &    & 
\backslash
mathbf{MT}_{s} 
\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{equation} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

The families of fibres 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathscr{F}_{\mathsf{X}^{K}}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathscr{G}_{\mathsf{w}}\}$
\end_inset

 are related by the 
\emph on
incidence relation
\emph default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\big(\mathsf{X}^{K},\mathsf{w}\big)\in\widetilde{\mathbf{P}'(\mathcal{S})}\quad\iff\quad\mathsf{w}\in\mathscr{F}(\mathsf{X}^{K})\quad\iff\quad\mathsf{X}^{K}\in\mathscr{G}(\mathsf{w}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To describe this explicitly,
 choose a representative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{W}^{I}=(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha})\in(\pi_{0})^{-1}(\mathsf{w})$
\end_inset

 and write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{X}^{K}=(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\big(\mathsf{X}^{K},[\mathsf{W}^{I}]\big)\in\widetilde{\mathbf{P}'(\mathcal{S})}\quad\iff\quad\mu_{\dot{A}}=\lambda^{A}X_{A\dot{A}},\;\psi^{\alpha}=\lambda^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These conditions depend only on the projective class 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathsf{W}^{I}]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Minitwistor Lines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The planar Yang-Mills amplitudes on minitwistor space localise precisely on certain rational curves called minitwistor lines\SpecialChar endofsentence
 Similarly,
 the worldsheet of our minitwistor sigma-model embeds into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 as such a line.
 We now characterise these special curves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hitchin1982twistor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "jones1984minitwistors"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 a 
\emph on
minitwistor line
\emph default
 is defined to be a rational curve whose normal bundle is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(2)$
\end_inset

.
 The hyperbolic superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

 parametrises all such lines.
 To each point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{x}\in\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

 we associate a unique minitwistor line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathsf{x}}\subset\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Denote its normal bundle by 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Nor}\,(\mathcal{L}_{\mathsf{x}})$
\end_inset

.
 Kodaira's theorem
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "kodaira1963structure"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 then identifies the tangent space of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{x}$
\end_inset

 with the space of global sections of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Nor\,}(\mathcal{L}_{\mathsf{x}})$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{\mathsf{x}}(\mathbf{H}_{s})\;\simeq\;\Gamma\big(\mathcal{L}(X,\theta);\text{Nor\,}(\mathcal{L}_{\mathsf{x}})\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{X}^{K}=(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 be a coordinate representative of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{x}\in\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 We define its associated minitwistor line by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)\coloneqq\upsilon\big(\mathscr{F}_{\mathsf{X}^{K}}\big)=\big\{\,\pi_{0}\big(\lambda^{A},\lambda^{A}X_{A\dot{A}},\lambda^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\big)\,\big|\,[\lambda^{A}]\in\mathbf{CP}^{1}\,\big\}.\label{eq:-160}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By construction,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)$
\end_inset

 is a rational curve in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 We now check that its normal bundle is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(2)$
\end_inset

,
 in accordance with the Hitchin-Jones definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First,
 project onto the bosonic component via
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{b}:\mathbf{MT}_{s}\longrightarrow\mathbf{MT}\subset\mathbf{CP}^{1}\times\mathbf{CP}^{1},\quad p_{b}(\mathsf{w})\;\coloneqq\;\big([\lambda^{A}],[\mu_{\dot{A}}]\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{b}$
\end_inset

 is the bosonic minitwistor line 
\begin_inset Formula $L(X)\coloneqq p_{b}\big(\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)\big)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the Veronese-type embedding
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V\colon\mathbf{MT}\longrightarrow\mathbf{CP}^{3},\quad V\big([\lambda^{A}],[\mu_{\dot{A}}]\big)\;\coloneqq\;[\lambda^{A}\mu_{\dot{A}}].
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Under 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

,
 the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $L(X)$
\end_inset

 becomes a nonsingular conic in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Any two such conics intersect in precisely two points,
 which implies that the normal bundle of 
\begin_inset Formula $L(X)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(2)$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that the normal bundle of the full supersymmetric line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 is also 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(2)$
\end_inset

,
 in agreement with the Hitchin-Jones definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now demonstrate that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

 indeed parametrises all minitwistor lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 We begin with the bosonic projection.
 On 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}\times\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

,
 the bosonic incidence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\dot{A}}=\lambda^{A}X_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 defines the intersection of the quadric 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathbf{MT})$
\end_inset

 with a hyperplane in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 A plane section is tangent to 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathbf{MT})$
\end_inset

 precisely when 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(X^{A\dot{A}})=0$
\end_inset

.
 If instead the section is non-tangent,
 then the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 is determined only up to an overall scale.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 denote the set of 
\emph on
non-tangent
\emph default
 hyperplane sections of 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathbf{MT})$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently,
 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is the space of non-null rays through the origin in complexified Minkowski space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}^{4}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is diffeomorphic to the projective model 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}$
\end_inset

 of complex hyperbolic space.
 It follows that,
 upon adjoining the fermionic dimensions,
 the full moduli superspace of minitwistor lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 is precisely 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}\simeq\mathbf{H}\times\mathbf{C}^{0|8}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
The Penrose Integrand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the minitwistor Penrose transform (Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Minitwistor-Correspondence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 one treats the minitwistor line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)$
\end_inset

 as a fibration over the Riemann sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 This formulation simplifies the construction of the top-forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)$
\end_inset

 needed in the Penrose integral formula.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{w}\in\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)$
\end_inset

 arises from a unique homogeneous coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $[\lambda^{A}]\in\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 via 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{w}=\pi_{0}(\lambda^{A},\lambda^{A}X_{A\dot{A}},\lambda^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

.
 Hence there is a natural projection
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{pr}_{\mathcal{L}}\colon\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)\longrightarrow\mathbf{CP}^{1},\quad\mathsf{w}\;\longmapsto\;[\lambda^{A}].
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This map realises 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)$
\end_inset

 as a holomorphic fibration over the Riemann sphere.
 An embedding of the celestial sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{CS}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)$
\end_inset

 is then equivalent to a section 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\Gamma(\mathbf{CP}^{1};\mathcal{L}(X,\theta))$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}s:T(\mathbf{CP}^{1})\to T(\mathcal{L}(X,\theta))$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fix integers 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq m,n\leq2$
\end_inset

.
 We define the restriction homomorphism
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}\colon\quad H^{m,n}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\,\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(p,q)\big)\;\longrightarrow\;H^{m,n}\big(\mathcal{L}(X,\theta);\,\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(p+q)\big)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}(\varphi)\coloneqq\varphi|_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}\;\coloneqq\;s^{*}(\varphi),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s\colon\mathbf{CP}^{1}\to\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)$
\end_inset

 is any holomorphic embedding.
 One checks easily that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}$
\end_inset

 is independent of the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}$
\end_inset

 carries a Dolbeault class on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 to the corresponding class on the line.
 Concretely,
 take the standard parametrisation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s\colon\mathbf{CP}^{1}\longrightarrow\mathcal{L}(X,\theta),\quad[\lambda^{A}]\;\mapsto\;\pi_{0}\big(\lambda^{A},\lambda^{A}X_{A\dot{A}},\lambda^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then a representative 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 restricts as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varphi|_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}(\lambda^{A})\;=\;\varphi(\lambda^{A},\lambda^{A}X_{A\dot{A}},\lambda^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To construct the Penrose integrand,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(p,q)$
\end_inset

-valued differential 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1)$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 We wish to build a top-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}[\varphi]\in\Omega^{1,1}(\mathcal{L}(X,\theta))$
\end_inset

 to serve as the integrand in the Penrose formula.
 Use the homogeneous coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $[\lambda^{A}]$
\end_inset

 on each fibre of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)\stackrel{\mathrm{pr}_{\mathcal{L}}}{\longrightarrow}\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 to define the holomorphic measure:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D\lambda\;\coloneqq\;\varepsilon_{AB}\,\lambda^{A}d\lambda^{B}\;\in\Omega^{1,0}\big(\mathcal{L}(X,\theta);\,\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(2)\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Restrict 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)$
\end_inset

 via the restriction homomorphism.
 Then set:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{f}[\varphi]\;\coloneqq\;D\lambda\,\wedge\,\varphi|_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}(\lambda^{A}).\label{eq:-161}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Under the rescaling 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A}\mapsto t\,\lambda^{A}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbf{C}_{*}$
\end_inset

),
 one finds 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}[\varphi]\mapsto t^{p+q+2}\,\boldsymbol{f}[\varphi]$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}[\varphi]$
\end_inset

 is a volume form precisely when 
\begin_inset Formula $p+q+2=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 define
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{f}\colon\Omega^{0,1}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\,\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(\Delta-2,-\Delta)\big)\,\longrightarrow\,\Omega^{1,1}\big(\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)\big),\quad\varphi\;\longmapsto\;\boldsymbol{f}[\varphi].
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This map sends a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(\Delta-2,-\Delta)$
\end_inset

-valued differential 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1)$
\end_inset

-form to the Penrose integrand on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Minitwistor Correspondence
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Minitwistor-Correspondence"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The minitwistor Penrose transform provides an isomorphism between Dolbeault cohomology classes on the homogeneous bundles over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 and solutions of the covariant wave equation on the hyperbolic superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular,
 it encodes bulk-to-boundary propagators on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

 in terms of cohomology data on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our primary aim in this section is to establish the Penrose machinery on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 This setup leads directly to the celestial BMSW identity.
 That identity will serve as the bridge between celestial amplitudes and holomorphic Wilson lines on minitwistor superspace.
 Equivalently,
 it allows us to generate celestial amplitudes as correlation functions of the minitwistor sigma-model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a further application,
 we employ the minitwistor Penrose transform to construct the celestial superwavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{\Delta}(\mathsf{X}^{K};\mathsf{Z}^{I})$
\end_inset

 for gluons in the spacetime representation.
 By the minitwistor correspondence,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 automatically satisfies the covariant wave equation on the hyperboloid 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Importantly,
 the argument 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{X}^{K}$
\end_inset

 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

,
 not in complexified Minkowski superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}^{4|8}$
\end_inset

.
 This reflects the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 is defined on the leaves of the hyperbolic foliation of Minkowski superspace used in the leaf amplitude formalism.
 In other words,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 is the
\emph on
 dimensionally reduced 
\emph default
wavefunction
\emph on
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
minitwistor Penrose transform
\emph default
 is the map
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{P}\colon\quad H^{0,1}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\,\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(\Delta-2,-\Delta)\big)\;\longrightarrow\;\Gamma\big(\mathbf{H}_{s};\,\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(-\Delta)\big)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{P}\varphi\;\coloneqq\;\int_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}\;\boldsymbol{f}\,[\varphi].\label{eq:-167}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}[\varphi]\in\Omega^{1,1}(\mathcal{L}(X,\theta))$
\end_inset

 is the Penrose integrand introduced in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-161"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Equivalently,
 writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{X}^{K}=(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 and using the explicit form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}[\varphi]$
\end_inset

,
 one has
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{P}\varphi\,\big(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\big)\;=\;\int_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}\;D\lambda\wedge\varphi\,|_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}\,(\lambda^{A}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Consistency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now verify consistency of the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 By construction (cf.
 end of Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Preliminaries"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}[\varphi]$
\end_inset

 is a top-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)$
\end_inset

 that is invariant under the fibre rescaling 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A}\mapsto t\,\lambda^{A}$
\end_inset

.
 Under the base rescaling 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A\dot{A}}\mapsto t\,X_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

,
 one finds 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}[\varphi]\mapsto t^{-\Delta}\,\boldsymbol{f}[\varphi]$
\end_inset

.
 This shows 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{P}\varphi\,\big(t\,X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\big)=t^{-\Delta}\,\mathcal{P}\varphi\,\big(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\big)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbf{C}_{*}$
\end_inset

,
 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\varphi\in\Gamma\big(\mathbf{H}_{s};\,\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(-\Delta)\big)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next,
 we check independence of representative.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 represent the same class in 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{0,1}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(\Delta-2,-\Delta)\big)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}=\varphi_{2}+\overline{\partial}\Lambda$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda\in\Omega^{0,0}(\mathbf{MT};\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(\Delta-2,-\Delta))$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{P}(\varphi_{1}-\varphi_{2})\;=\;\int_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}\;D\lambda\wedge\overline{\partial}\Lambda|_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}(\lambda^{A})=0,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\partial}\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is exact on each fibre.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 is well-defined on Dolbeault cohomology classes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Differential Equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A simple yet important consequence of the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 is the following differential identity.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $[\varphi]\in H^{0,1}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(\Delta-2,-\Delta)\big)$
\end_inset

 be any representative.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is holomorphic (
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\partial}\,\varphi=0$
\end_inset

),
 the chain rule on the restriction to the line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)$
\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla_{A\dot{A}}\,\varphi|_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}\,(\lambda^{A})\;=\;\lambda_{A}\,\frac{\partial\varphi}{\partial\mu^{\dot{A}}}\Bigg|_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Moreover,
 dominated convergence and the mean-value theorem justify exchanging 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 with the integral defining the Penrose transform.
 Hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla_{A\dot{A}}\,\mathcal{P}\varphi\;=\;\int_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}\;D\lambda\wedge\lambda_{A}\,\frac{\partial\varphi}{\partial\mu^{\dot{A}}}\Bigg|_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Acting once more with 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 then yields the partial differential equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla^{A\dot{A}}\nabla_{A\dot{A}}\,\mathcal{P}\varphi\;=\;0.\label{eq:-162}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Proper Functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our aim is to reformulate Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-162"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) as a covariant wave equation on hyperbolic superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 To that end,
 we introduce the following definition.
 A section 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 of the homogeneous bundle over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

 is said to define a 
\emph on
proper function
\emph default
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{L}_{\xi}\,\Phi=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Penrose transform then lifts to a map
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{P}_{*}\colon\quad H^{0,1}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\,\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(\Delta-2,-\Delta)\big)\;\longrightarrow\;\mathscr{C}^{\infty}(\mathbf{H}_{s})
\end{equation}

\end_inset

defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{P}_{*}[\varphi]\;\coloneqq\;\Vert X\Vert^{\Delta}\,\int_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}\;\boldsymbol{f}[\varphi].
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{\Delta}\coloneqq\mathcal{P}_{*}[\varphi]$
\end_inset

.
 A direct computation shows
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla^{A\dot{A}}\nabla_{A\dot{A}}\,\big(\Vert X\Vert^{-\Delta}\,\Phi_{\Delta}(X_{B\dot{B}},\theta_{C}^{\alpha})\big)\;=\;0.\label{eq:-163}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The remaining task is to prove that this equation is equivalent to the eigenvalue problem for the Beltrami-Laplace operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\square_{\mathbf{H}}$
\end_inset

 on the hyperbolic space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
A Simple Lemma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The link between Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-163"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and the spectral theory of the wave operator on hyperbolic space is introduced by the following result.
 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{J}_{A\dot{A}B\dot{B}}\;\coloneqq\;-i\left(X_{A\dot{A}}\frac{\partial}{\partial X^{B\dot{B}}}-X_{B\dot{B}}\frac{\partial}{\partial X^{A\dot{A}}}\right)\label{eq:-164}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

be the generator of the Lie algebra of isometries of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\partial/\partial X^{A\dot{A}}\}$
\end_inset

 is the coordinate frame.
 Define the quadratic Casimir operator by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{Q}\;\coloneqq\;\frac{1}{2}\mathcal{J}_{A\dot{A}B\dot{B}}\mathcal{J}^{A\dot{A}B\dot{B}}.\label{eq:-165}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then for every proper function 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{\Delta}\in\mathscr{C}^{\infty}(\mathbf{H}_{s})$
\end_inset

 one has the equivalence:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla^{A\dot{A}}\nabla_{A\dot{A}}\,\big(\Vert X\Vert^{-\Delta}\,\Phi_{\Delta}\big)\;=\;0\quad\iff\quad\square_{\mathbf{H}}\Phi_{\Delta}\;=\;\Delta(\Delta-2)\Phi_{\Delta}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To establish this result,
 we first expand the left-hand side of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-163"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Vert X\Vert^{2}\,\nabla^{A\dot{A}}\nabla_{A\dot{A}}\,\Phi_{\Delta}+2\Delta\,\mathscr{L}_{\xi}\Phi_{\Delta}\;=\;\Delta(\Delta-2)\,\Phi_{\Delta}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 is assumed proper (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{L}_{\xi}\,\Phi_{\Delta}=0$
\end_inset

),
 this reduces to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Vert X\Vert^{2}\,\nabla^{A\dot{A}}\nabla_{A\dot{A}}\Phi_{\Delta}\;=\;\Delta(\Delta-2)\,\Phi_{\Delta}.\label{eq:-166}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand,
 a direct computation of the Casimir operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}$
\end_inset

 using Eqs.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-164"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-165"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{Q}\,\Phi_{\Delta}\;=\;\Vert X\Vert^{2}\,\nabla^{A\dot{A}}\nabla_{A\dot{A}}\,\Phi_{\Delta}+2\,X^{A\dot{A}}\nabla_{A\dot{A}}\,\Phi_{\Delta}+X^{A\dot{A}}\nabla_{A\dot{A}}\big(X^{B\dot{B}}\nabla_{B\dot{B}}\Phi_{\Delta}\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It follows that Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-166"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) is equivalent to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{Q}\,\Phi_{\Delta}\;=\;\Delta(\Delta-2)\,\Phi_{\Delta}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Finally,
 the lemma follows from the well-known result (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "fronsdal1974elementary"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) that on homogeneous spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}=\square_{\mathbf{H}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Main Result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The preceding lemma implies that the modified minitwistor Penrose transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{*}$
\end_inset

 sends 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\partial}$
\end_inset

-cohomology classes on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 to solutions of the eigenvalue problem for the Beltrami-Laplace operator on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 We now formalise this statement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be any differentiable manifold and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T\colon\mathscr{C}^{\infty}}(U)\to\mathscr{C}^{\infty}(U)$
\end_inset

 be a linear differential operator.
 We define its kernel by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{ker}\,(U;\mathcal{T})\;\coloneqq\;\big\{\,\Phi\in\mathscr{C}^{\infty}(U)\,\big|\,\mathcal{T}\Phi=0\,\big\}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{P}_{*}\big(H^{0,1}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\,\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(\Delta-2,-\Delta)\big)\big)\;\subseteq\;\mathrm{ker}\big(\mathbf{H}_{s};\,\square_{\mathbf{H}}-\Delta(\Delta-2)\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Furthermore,
 the invertibility of the X-ray transform on projective spaces (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gel_fand2003selected"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) and a homological argument yield a stronger result
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "jones1984minitwistors"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bailey1998twistor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H^{0,1}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\,\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(\Delta-2,-\Delta)\big)\;\simeq\;\mathrm{ker}\big(\mathbf{H}_{s};\,\square_{\mathbf{H}}-\Delta(\Delta-2)\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that the integral transform in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-167"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) admits an explicit inversion in the form of a Leray residue formula.
 This construction builds on Gindikin's analyses of the Radon and John's transforms (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gindikin1990cauchy,gindikin2007second,gindikin2014inversion"
literal "false"

\end_inset

),
 the Cauchy-Fantappié formula,
 and Leray's theory of multidimensional residues.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Celestial Superwavefunction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest non-trivial application of the minitwistor correspondence is the derivation of the celestial superwavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{\Delta}(\mathsf{X}^{K};\mathsf{Z}^{I})$
\end_inset

 from the minitwistor wavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}(\mathsf{W}^{I};\mathsf{Z}^{I})$
\end_inset

.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 is a distribution on hyperbolic superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}$
\end_inset

 is a current on minitwistor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 These are related by a suitable modification of the Penrose transform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "d1996radon"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 generalised the Penrose transform from its standard double-fibration formulation over flag manifolds to the setting of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{D}$
\end_inset

-modules.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "david2003x"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 then applied their theory to currents of differential forms valued in vector bundles.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "voronov1991geometric"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 provided a detailed extension of geometric integration theory to supermanifolds
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For a review,
 cf.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "witten2012notes"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Using this framework,
 we lift the minitwistor Penrose transform to the supercurrent category and denote the resulting map by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{P}'\colon\quad\mathscr{D}'_{0,1}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\,\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(\Delta-2,-\Delta)\big)\;\longrightarrow\;\mathscr{D}'(\mathbf{H}_{s}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{D}'(\mathbf{H}_{s})$
\end_inset

 is the module of distributions on the supermanifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 The covariant wave operator acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{D}'(\mathbf{H}_{s})$
\end_inset

 by duality,
 and we denote its kernel by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{ker}'\big(\mathbf{H}_{s};\,\square_{\mathbf{H}}-\Delta(\Delta-2)\big)\;\coloneqq\;\big\{\,\omega\in\mathscr{D}'(\mathbf{H}_{s})\,\big|\,\square_{\mathbf{H}}\,\omega\;=\;\Delta(\Delta-2)\,\omega\,\big\}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The minitwistor correspondence in the current-distribution category now reads:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{0,1}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\,\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(\Delta-2,-\Delta)\big)\;\simeq\;\mathrm{ker}'\big(\mathbf{H}_{s};\,\square_{\mathbf{H}}-\Delta(\Delta-2)\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fix a dual minitwistor 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathsf{Z}^{I}]\in\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The representative superwavefunction
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi_{\Delta}^{2}\big(\,\cdot\,;\mathsf{Z}^{I}\big)\in\mathscr{D}'_{0,1}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\,\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(\Delta-2,-\Delta)\big)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

lies in the domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}'$
\end_inset

.
 We therefore define the 
\emph on
celestial superwavefunction
\emph default
 for gluons of conformal weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Phi_{\Delta}\big(\,\cdot\,;\mathsf{Z}^{I}\big)\in\mathscr{D}'(\mathbf{H}_{s}),\quad\Phi_{\Delta}\big(\,\cdot\,;\mathsf{Z}^{I}\big)\;\coloneqq\;\mathcal{P}'\big[\Psi_{\Delta}^{2}(\,\cdot\,;\mathsf{Z}^{I})\big].
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Explicitly,
 one has:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Phi_{\Delta}\big(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha};\mathsf{Z}^{I}\big)\;=\;\Vert X\Vert^{\Delta}\,\int_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}\;D\lambda\wedge\Psi_{\Delta}^{2}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}\big(\lambda^{A};\mathsf{Z}^{I}\big).\label{eq:-168}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The restriction of a minitwistor superwavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}$
\end_inset

 to the line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)$
\end_inset

 is the supercurrent
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}\big(\,\cdot\,;\mathsf{Z}^{I}\big)\in\mathscr{D}'_{0,1}\big(\mathcal{L}(X,\theta);\,\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(-p)\big)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}\big(\lambda^{A};\mathsf{Z}^{I}\big)\;=\;\overline{\delta}_{p-\Delta}(z^{A},\lambda^{A})\,\frac{\mathcal{C}(\Delta)}{\langle\lambda|X|\bar{z}]^{\Delta}}\,\exp\left(i\frac{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }\langle\lambda|\theta\cdot\eta\rangle\right).\label{eq:-169}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Substituting into the Penrose integral (Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-168"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

)) yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Phi_{\Delta}\big(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha};\mathsf{Z}^{I}\big)\;=\;K_{\Delta}\big(X_{A\dot{A}};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}}\big)\,e^{i\langle z|\theta\cdot\eta\rangle},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the bulk-to-boundary propagator 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K_{\Delta}\big(X_{A\dot{A}};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}}\big)\;=\;\frac{\mathcal{C}(\Delta)}{\langle z|\mathcal{R}|\bar{z}]^{\Delta}},\quad\mathcal{R}_{A\dot{A}}\;=\;\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\Vert X\Vert}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The physical interpretation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 proceeds via its relation to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 conformal primary wavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

.
 This wavefunction is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi_{\Delta}(x^{\mu},\theta_{A}^{\alpha};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}},\eta^{\alpha})\;=\;\frac{\Gamma(\Delta)}{(\varepsilon-iq(z,\bar{z})\cdot x)^{\Delta}}\,e^{i\langle z|\theta\cdot\eta\rangle},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\mu}(z,\bar{z})\coloneqq z^{A}(\sigma^{\mu})_{A\dot{A}}\bar{z}^{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 is the standard null four-vector.
 The superwavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 describes a gluon of conformal weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 and helicity state 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 It is obtained by extending the analyses of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "banerjee2019null,banerjee2019symmetries,banerjee2020conformal,banerjee2020conformal1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to the Lorentz 
\emph on
supergroup
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dimensional reduction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 onto the leaves of the hyperbolic foliation of Klein superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{K}^{4|8}\subset\mathbf{C}^{4|8}$
\end_inset

 yields the celestial superwavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 is obtained by restricting 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 to each hyperbolic slice in the leaf amplitude formalism
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "banerjee2025worldsheet"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 An important property of the family 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\Phi_{\Delta}\}$
\end_inset

 follows from the analysis of the spectral theory for primary fields in the 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

-WZNW model
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "teschner1997conformal,teschner1999mini,teschner1999structure,teschner2000operator,ribault2005h3+"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\Phi_{\Delta}\}$
\end_inset

 is both complete and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

-function orthonormal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Boels-Mason-Skinner-Witten 
\emph on
(BMSW)
\emph default
 Identity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Building on the constructions of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "boels2007supersymmetric"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "witten2004perturbative"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 we now derive the central result of this subsection.
 We refer to this as the celestial Boels-Mason-Skinner-Witten (BMSW) identity.
 It takes the form of an integral formula equating the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-fold minitwistor Penrose transform of the superwavefunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}^{p}$
\end_inset

,
 weighted by a Lie-algebra-valued logarithmic differential form,
 with the kernel of the Mellin-transformed Parke-Taylor factors appearing in the celestial leaf amplitudes for gluonic scattering.
 This identity will serve as our key formula for both geometric and dynamical interpretations of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM celestial amplitudes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To derive the integral identity,
 fix a dual minitwistor point 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathsf{Z}^{I}]\in\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

,
 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{W}^{I}=(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 parametrise minitwistor superspace.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{G}$
\end_inset

 be a compact,
 simply-connected and semisimple Lie group with Lie algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a Lie-algebra-valued section
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g^{\mathsf{a}}\in\Gamma\big(\mathbf{CP}^{1};\mathfrak{g}\otimes\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(-2)\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the BMSW identity,
 we use the minitwistor wavefunction
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi_{\Delta}^{0}\big(\,\cdot\,;\mathsf{Z}^{I}\big)\in\mathscr{D}'_{0,1}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\,\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(\Delta,-\Delta)\big),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which we abbreviate by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the Lie-algebra-valued supercurrent
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{K}_{\Delta,g}^{\mathsf{a}}\in\mathscr{D}'_{0,1}\big(\mathbf{MT}_{s};\,\mathfrak{g}\otimes\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(\Delta-2,-\Delta)\big)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{K}_{\Delta,g}^{\mathsf{a}}\big(\mathsf{W}^{I}\big)\;\coloneqq\;g^{\mathsf{a}}(\lambda^{A})\,\Psi_{\Delta}\big(\mathsf{W}^{I};\mathsf{Z}^{I'}\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here and below we omit the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\otimes$
\end_inset

 for simple juxtaposition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}_{\Delta,g}^{\mathsf{a}}$
\end_inset

 lies in the domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}'$
\end_inset

,
 we may write the Penrose integral as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{P}'\big[\mathcal{K}_{\Delta,g}^{\mathsf{a}}\big]\,\big(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\big)\;=\;\int_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}\;D\lambda\wedge g^{\mathsf{a}}(\lambda^{A})\,\Psi_{\Delta}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}(\lambda^{A};\mathsf{Z}^{I}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Using the restriction formula in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-169"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 we find that the Penrose integral evaluates to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}\;D\lambda\wedge g^{\mathsf{a}}(\lambda^{A})\,\Psi_{\Delta}\,|_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}(\lambda^{A};\mathsf{Z}^{I})\;=\;\frac{\mathcal{C}(\Delta)}{\langle z|X|\bar{z}]^{\Delta}}\,e^{i\langle z|\theta\cdot\eta\rangle}\,g^{\mathsf{a}}(z^{A}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Define the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-fold Cartesian product of the minitwistor line by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{n}\coloneqq\bigtimes{}^{n}\;\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)$
\end_inset

.
 An inductive argument then shows that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\mathcal{L}_{n}\,\,\,}{\int}\;\bigwedge_{i=1}^{n}\;D\lambda_{i}\wedge g^{\mathsf{a}_{i}}(\lambda_{i}^{A})\,\Psi_{\Delta_{i}}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}\big(\lambda^{A};\mathsf{Z}^{I}\big)\;=\;\prod_{i=1}^{n}\;\frac{\mathcal{C}(\Delta_{i})}{\langle z_{i}|X|\bar{z}_{i}]^{\Delta_{i}}}\,e^{i\langle z_{i}|\theta\cdot\eta_{i}\rangle}\,g^{\mathsf{a}_{i}}(\lambda_{i}^{A}).\label{eq:-170}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Next,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathsf{T}^{\mathsf{a}}\}$
\end_inset

 be a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

.
 Define
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g^{\mathsf{a}_{i}}(\lambda_{i}^{A})\;=\;\frac{\mathsf{T}^{\mathsf{a}_{i}}}{\lambda_{i}\cdot\lambda_{i+1}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Introduce the Lie-algebra-valued logarithmic differential form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\omega}^{\mathsf{a}_{i}}(\lambda_{i}^{A})\;\coloneqq\;\mathsf{T}^{\mathsf{a}_{i}}\,\frac{D\lambda_{i}}{\lambda_{i}\cdot\lambda_{i+1}}.\label{eq:-178}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-170"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) reduces to the 
\emph on
supersymmetric
\emph default
 
\emph on
celestial BMSW identity
\emph default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\mathcal{L}_{n}\,\,\,}{\int}\;\bigwedge_{i=1}^{n}\;\boldsymbol{\omega}^{\mathsf{a}_{i}}(\lambda_{i}^{A})\wedge\Psi_{\Delta_{i}}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)}\big(\lambda_{i}^{A};\mathsf{Z}_{i}^{I}\big)\;=\;\prod_{i=1}^{n}\;\frac{\mathcal{C}(\Delta_{i})}{\langle z_{i}|X|\bar{z}_{i}]^{\Delta_{i}}}\,e^{i\langle z_{i}|\theta\cdot\eta_{i}\rangle}\,\frac{\mathsf{T}^{\mathsf{a}_{i}}}{z_{i}\cdot z_{i+1}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Supersymmetric Celestial RSVW Identity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the preceding subsection,
 we derived the integral kernel for the Mellin-transformed Parke-Taylor factors,
 namely
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\prod_{i=1}^{n}\;\frac{\mathcal{C}(\Delta_{i})}{\langle z_{i}|X|\bar{z}_{i}]^{\Delta_{i}}}\,e^{i\langle z_{i}|\theta\cdot\eta_{i}\rangle}\,\frac{\mathsf{T}^{\mathsf{a}_{i}}}{z_{i}\cdot z_{i+1}}\,,\label{eq:-182}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

as an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-fold Penrose transform of the minitwistor superwavefunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

.
 We called this the supersymmetric celestial BMSW identity.
 It provides a direct map from celestial leaf amplitudes to correlation functions in the minitwistor sigma-model,
 via the power-series expansion of the Quillen determinant line bundle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now develop a complementary formulation by translating celestial leaf amplitudes into minitwistor amplitudes.
 Direct evaluation of the minitwistor transform on distributional data is challenging.
 Instead,
 we will derive a convenient rewriting of the identity resolution.
 Substituting this into the leaf amplitudes then produces their minitwistor counterparts in a systematic manner.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our approach follows 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "roiban2004googly,roiban2004tree,roiban2005dissolving"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "witten2004perturbative"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In contrast to the BMSW identity,
 where one integrates the superwavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 over the minitwistor line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)$
\end_inset

,
 we impose the supersymmetric incidence relations directly on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{\dot{A}}=\lambda^{A}\,X_{A\dot{A}},\quad\psi^{\alpha}=\lambda^{A}\,\theta_{A}^{\alpha}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These relations are enforced via delta ``functions'' on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 The resulting multidimensional minitwistor transform reproduces the Parke-Taylor kernel of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-182"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 We term this the 
\emph on
supersymmetric celestial Roiban-Spradlin-Volovich-Witten
\emph default
 (RSVW) 
\emph on
identity
\emph default
.
 Its bosonic version first appeared in Mol (2025).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Preliminaries
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imposing the incidence relations on minitwistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 via distributions (or,
 more precisely,
 via currents of differential forms) is subtler than in standard projective twistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{PT}^{3|4}$
\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

,
 the spinor coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 carry independent scaling weights.
 We must however construct the integrand as a 
\emph on
legitimate
\emph default
 differential form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

,
 rather than merely as a section of the homogeneous bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(p,q)$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover,
 the form must have the correct bi-degree in the exterior algebra of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We therefore dedicate this first subsection to a careful construction of the integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 of the superwavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 that properly implements the incidence relations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We again consider a compact,
 simply-connected,
 semisimple gauge group 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{G}$
\end_inset

 with Lie algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a Lie-algebra-valued section 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\mathsf{a}}\in\Gamma(\mathbf{CP}^{1};\mathfrak{g}\otimes\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(-2)).$
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}_{\Delta,g}^{\mathsf{a}}$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,1)$
\end_inset

-supercurrent on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 defined by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{k}_{\Delta,g}^{\mathsf{a}}\;\coloneqq\;g^{\mathsf{a}}(\lambda^{A})\;\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}\big(\mu_{\dot{A}},\lambda^{A}X_{A\dot{A}}\big)\wedge\delta^{0|4}\big(\psi^{\alpha}-\lambda^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\big)\wedge D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Under the rescaling
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathsf{W}^{I}\;\longmapsto\;\mathsf{W}'^{I}\coloneqq(t_{1}\,\lambda^{A},t_{2}\,\mu_{\dot{A}},t_{1}\,\psi^{\alpha}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

one checks
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{k}_{\Delta,g}^{\mathsf{a}}\;\longmapsto\;t_{1}^{-\Delta}t_{2}^{\Delta}\,\boldsymbol{k}_{\Delta,g}^{\mathsf{a}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}_{\Delta,g}^{\mathsf{a}}$
\end_inset

 defines an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathfrak{g}}(-\Delta,\Delta)$
\end_inset

-valued supercurrent of bi-degree 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now fix a dual minitwistor 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathsf{Z}^{I}]\in\mathbf{MT}_{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The superwavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}\coloneqq\Psi_{\Delta}^{0}$
\end_inset

 transforms under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{W}^{I}\mapsto\mathsf{W}'^{I}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi_{\Delta}\big(\mathsf{W}^{I};\mathsf{Z}^{I}\big)\;\longmapsto\;t_{1}^{\Delta}t_{2}^{-\Delta}\,\Psi_{\Delta}\big(\mathsf{W}^{I};\mathsf{Z}^{I}\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{V}_{\Delta,g}^{\mathsf{a}}\;\coloneqq\,\Psi_{\Delta}\big(\mathsf{W}^{I};\mathsf{Z}^{I}\big)\wedge\boldsymbol{k}_{\Delta,g}^{\mathsf{a}}\big(\mathsf{W}^{I};\mathsf{X}^{K}\big)\label{eq:-180}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

defines a bi-degree 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,2)$
\end_inset

 supercurrent on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 that is invariant under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{W}^{I}\mapsto\mathsf{W}'^{I}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{MT}_{s}\subset\mathbf{CP}^{1|4}\times\mathbf{CP}^{1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1|4}\times\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is compact,
 any smooth proper function 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi\colon\mathbf{MT}_{s}\to\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{L}_{\xi}\Phi=0$
\end_inset

) serves as a test form of bi-degree 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)$
\end_inset

.
 In particular,
 choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 to be the characteristic function 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\chi}$
\end_inset

 of the quadric,
 we regard 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{\Delta,g}^{\mathsf{a}}$
\end_inset

 as a 
\emph on
volume form
\emph default
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence the integral
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle\mathcal{V}_{\Delta,g}^{\mathsf{a}},\boldsymbol{\chi}\rangle=\underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}\,\,\,}{\int}\mathcal{V}_{\Delta,g}^{\mathsf{a}}\;=\;\underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}\,\,\,}{\int}\Psi_{\Delta}\big(\mathsf{W}^{I};\mathsf{Z}^{I'}\big)\wedge\boldsymbol{k}_{\Delta,g}^{\mathsf{a}}\big(\mathsf{W}^{I};\mathsf{X}^{K}\big)\label{eq:-181}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is well-defined.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting the explicit form of the superwavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 (Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-39"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

)) into the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{\Delta,g}^{\mathsf{a}}$
\end_inset

 (Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-180"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

)),
 we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{V}_{\Delta,g}^{\mathsf{a}} & =g^{\mathsf{a}}(\lambda^{A})\;\frac{\mathcal{C}(\Delta)}{[\mu\bar{z}]^{\Delta}}\,\exp\left(i\frac{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }\psi\cdot\eta\right)\;\overline{\delta}_{-\Delta}\big(z^{A},\lambda^{A}\big)\wedge\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}\big(\mu_{\dot{A}},\lambda^{A}\,X_{A\dot{A}}\big)\\
 & \quad\wedge\delta^{0|4}\big(\psi^{\alpha}-\lambda^{A}\,\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\big)\wedge D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

The integral in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-181"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) then evaluates to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}\,\,\,}{\int}D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}\quad\Psi_{\Delta}\big(\mathsf{W}^{I};\mathsf{Z}^{I'}\big)\;\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}\big(\mu_{\dot{A}},\lambda^{A}\,X_{A\dot{A}}\big)\,\delta^{0|4}\big(\psi^{\alpha}-\lambda^{A}\,\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\big)\;g^{\mathsf{a}}(\lambda^{A})\label{eq:-176}\\
 & \quad=\;\frac{\mathcal{C}(\Delta)}{\langle z|X|\bar{z}]^{\Delta}}\,e^{i\langle z|\theta\cdot\eta\rangle}\,g^{\mathsf{a}}(z^{A}).\label{eq:-175}
\end{align}

\end_inset

We have denoted wedge products by juxtaposition for compactness.
 By construction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{\Delta,g}^{\mathsf{a}}$
\end_inset

,
 this integral is projectively well-defined.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
A Simple Lemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next step is to unify the delta-currents in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-176"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) into the minitwistor delta 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\delta}_{\Delta_{1},\Delta_{2}}^{2|4}$
\end_inset

 introduced in Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Completeness-Relation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 (Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-179"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

)).
 We achieve this via the following result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Lemma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Y}^{I}\colon\mathbf{CP}^{1}\to\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)\subset\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 be the embedding of the holomorphic celestial sphere into the minitwistor line,
 defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathsf{Y}^{I}\big(\sigma^{A}\big)\;\coloneqq\;\big(\sigma^{A},\sigma^{A}\,X_{A\dot{A}},\sigma^{A}\,\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By construction,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Y}^{I}$
\end_inset

 is a global section of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)\to\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

,
 and its differential 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{d}\mathsf{Y}^{I}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism on tangent spaces.
 Hence each point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{w}\in\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a unique projective spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $[\sigma^{A}]\in\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 We use these homogeneous coordinates to orient 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)$
\end_inset

.
 Explicitly,
 we define the holomorphic measure:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D\sigma\;\in\;\Omega^{1,0}\big(\mathcal{L}(X,\theta);\,\mathcal{O}_{\mathbf{C}}(2)\big),\quad D\sigma\coloneqq\varepsilon_{AB}\,\sigma^{A}\,d\sigma^{B}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

With these preparations,
 the following equality of currents holds on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(X,\theta)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}\big(\mu_{\dot{A}},\lambda^{A}\,X_{A\dot{A}}\big)\,\delta^{0|4}\big(\psi^{\alpha}-\lambda^{A}\,\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\big)\;g^{\mathsf{a}}(\lambda^{A})=\underset{\mathbf{CP}^{1}\,\,\,}{\int}D\sigma\;g^{\mathsf{a}}(\sigma^{A})\;\wedge\;\overline{\delta}_{-\Delta,\Delta}^{2|4}\big(\mathsf{W}^{I};\,\mathsf{Y}^{I'}(\sigma^{A})\big).\label{eq:-177}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Proof of Lemma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first step uses the resolution of identity for the holomorphic delta 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\delta}^{2}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We rewrite the left-hand side as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \overline{\delta}_{\Delta}\big(\mu_{\dot{A}},\lambda^{A}\,X_{A\dot{A}}\big)\,\delta^{0|4}\big(\psi^{\alpha}-\lambda^{A}\,\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\big)\;g^{\mathsf{a}}(\lambda^{A})\label{eq:-171}\\
 & \quad=\;\underset{\mathbf{C}^{2}\,\,\,}{\int}d^{2}s\;\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(\lambda^{A}-s^{A}\big)\,\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}\big(\mu_{\dot{A}},s^{A}\,X_{A\dot{A}}\big)\,\delta^{0|4}\big(\psi^{\alpha}-s^{A}\,\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\big)\;g^{\mathsf{a}}(s^{A}).\label{eq:-172}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Next we parametrise 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{A}=t\,\sigma^{A}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbf{C}_{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[\sigma^{A}]\in\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The measure decomposes as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d^{2}s\;=\;D\sigma\,\wedge\,\frac{dt}{t}\;t^{2},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-172"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) becomes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \overline{\delta}_{\Delta}\big(\mu_{\dot{A}},\lambda^{A}\,X_{A\dot{A}}\big)\,\delta^{0|4}\big(\psi^{\alpha}-\lambda^{A}\,\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\big)\;g^{\mathsf{a}}(\lambda^{A})\\
 & =\underset{\mathbf{CP}^{1}\,\,\,}{\int}D\sigma\;\underset{\mathbf{C}_{*}\,\,\,}{\int}\frac{dt}{t}\;t^{-\Delta}\,\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(\lambda^{A}-t\sigma^{A}\big)\,\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}\big(\mu_{\dot{A}},\sigma^{A}\,X_{A\dot{A}}\big)\,\delta^{0|4}\big(\psi^{\alpha}-t\sigma^{A}\,\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\big)\;g^{\mathsf{a}}(\sigma^{A}).
\end{align}

\end_inset

Carrying out the 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

-integral yields the minitwistor delta 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\delta}_{-\Delta,\Delta}^{2|4}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \overline{\delta}_{\Delta}\big(\mu_{\dot{A}},\lambda^{A}\,X_{A\dot{A}}\big)\,\delta^{0|4}\big(\psi^{\alpha}-\lambda^{A}\,\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\big)\;g^{\mathsf{a}}(\lambda^{A})\label{eq:-173}\\
 & =\underset{\mathbf{CP}^{1}\,\,\,}{\int}D\sigma\;g^{\mathsf{a}}(\sigma^{A})\;\wedge\;\overline{\delta}_{-\Delta,\Delta}^{2|4}\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha}\big|\sigma^{A},\sigma^{A}\,X_{A\dot{A}},\sigma^{A}\,\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\big).\label{eq:-174}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{W}^{I}=(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\psi^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Y}^{I}(\sigma^{A})$
\end_inset

 into Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-174"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) completes the proof of the lemma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Main Result
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are now ready to present the main result of this subsection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting the lemma's identity (Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-177"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

)) into the integral of the top-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{\Delta,g}^{\mathsf{a}}$
\end_inset

 (Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-176"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

)) yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \underset{\mathbf{MT}_{s}\,\,\,}{\int}D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}\;\Psi_{\Delta}\big(\mathsf{W}^{I};\mathsf{Z}^{I}\big)\;\underset{\mathbf{CP}^{1}\,\,\,}{\int}D\sigma\;g^{\mathsf{a}}(\sigma^{A})\;\wedge\;\overline{\delta}_{-\Delta,\Delta}^{2|4}\big(\mathsf{W}^{I};\mathsf{Y}^{I'}(\sigma^{A})\big)\\
 & =\;\frac{\mathcal{C}(\Delta)}{\langle z|X|\bar{z}]^{\Delta}}\,e^{i\langle z|\theta\cdot\eta\rangle}\,g^{\mathsf{a}}(z^{A}).
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We extend this to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 insertions by defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}_{n}\coloneqq\bigtimes^{n}\mathbf{MT}_{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{L}_{n}\coloneqq\bigtimes^{n}\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 An inductive argument then gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \underset{\mathbf{X}_{n}\,}{\int}\bigwedge_{i=1}^{n}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}_{i}\;\Psi_{\Delta_{i}}\big(\mathsf{W}_{i}^{I};\mathsf{Z}_{i}^{I'}\big)\;\underset{\mathbf{L}_{n}\,}{\int}\bigwedge_{j=1}^{n}\,D\sigma_{j}\;g^{\mathsf{a}_{j}}(\sigma_{j}^{A})\;\wedge\;\overline{\delta}_{-\Delta_{j},\Delta_{j}}^{2|4}\big(\mathsf{W}_{j}^{J};\,\mathsf{Y}^{J'}(\sigma_{j}^{A})\big)\\
 & =\;\prod_{i=1}^{n}\,\frac{\mathcal{C}(\Delta_{i})}{\langle z_{i}|X|\bar{z}_{i}]^{\Delta_{i}}}\,e^{i\langle z_{i}|\theta\cdot\eta_{i}\rangle}\,g^{\mathsf{a}_{i}}(z_{i}^{A}).
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 choosing a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathsf{T}^{\mathsf{a}_{i}}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

 and setting
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g^{\mathsf{a}_{i}}(\sigma^{A})\;=\;\frac{\mathsf{T}^{\mathsf{a}_{i}}}{\sigma_{i}\cdot\sigma_{i+1}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

we find,
 via the logarithmic form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{\mathsf{a}_{i}}(\sigma_{i}^{A})$
\end_inset

 of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-178"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
supersymmetric celestial RSVW identity
\emph default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \underset{\mathbf{X}_{n}\,}{\int}\bigwedge_{i=1}^{n}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{W}_{i}\;\Psi_{\Delta_{i}}\big(\mathsf{W}_{i}^{I};\mathsf{Z}_{i}^{I'}\big)\;\underset{\mathbf{L}_{n}\,}{\int}\bigwedge_{j=1}^{n}\,\boldsymbol{\omega}^{\mathsf{a}_{j}}(\sigma_{j}^{A})\;\wedge\;\overline{\delta}_{-\Delta_{j},\Delta_{j}}^{2|4}\big(\mathsf{W}_{j}^{J};\,\mathsf{Y}^{J'}(\sigma_{j}^{A})\big)\\
 & =\;\prod_{i=1}^{n}\,\frac{\mathcal{C}(\Delta_{i})}{\langle z_{i}|X|\bar{z}_{i}]^{\Delta_{i}}}\,e^{i\langle z_{i}|\theta\cdot\eta_{i}\rangle}\,\frac{\mathsf{T}^{\mathsf{a}_{i}}}{z_{i}\cdot z_{i+1}}.
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This formula serves as the key entry in our dictionary between celestial and minitwistor amplitudes for gluons in planar Yang-Mills theory.
 It provides the link between gluonic amplitudes and the holonomies of the Knizhnik-Zamolodchikov connection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Tree-level 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-Matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The on-shell BCFW recursion relations
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "britto2005direct,britto2005new,bianchi2008generating,brandhuber2008note,arkani2010simplest,elvang2009recursion"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM theory admit an explicit solution known as the Drummond-Henn representation
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cf.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "drummond2009all,dixon2011all,korchemsky2010twistor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This solution provides a compact,
 manifestly supersymmetric expression for the tree-level superamplitude.
 From it one may extract purely gluonic amplitudes valid in any gauge theory.
 Remarkably,
 the Drummond-Henn formula is written in terms of nested sums of dual-conformal 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-invariants,
 thus making both standard and dual superconformal symmetries manifest.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this subsection,
 we employ the Drummond-Henn solution for tree-level 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{k}$
\end_inset

-MHV superamplitudes to derive the corresponding sectional/leaf amplitudes in terms of minitwistor superwavefunctions.
 Our strategy consists of two main steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We write an integral representation of each 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-invariant via the Fadde'ev-Popov method,
 such that all frequency dependence appears as exponential factors.
 The resulting representation admits a straightforward Mellin transform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We combine the Fadde'ev-Popov representation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-invariant with the celestial RSVW identity.
 The resulting expression is the tree-level 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{k}$
\end_inset

-MHV minitwistor amplitude,
 given by an integral over the moduli space parametrising configurations of 
\begin_inset Formula $2k+1$
\end_inset

 minitwistor lines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin by deriving in detail the 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{1}$
\end_inset

- and 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{2}$
\end_inset

-MHV amplitudes.
 We then extend the construction inductively to obtain the full tree-level celestial 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

-matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $N^{1}$
\end_inset

-MHV Scattering Amplitude
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:N-MHV-Scattering-Amplitude"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 supersymmetric Yang-Mills (SYM) theory on four-dimensional Klein space
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Kleinian metric in global rectangular coordinates is:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{\mu\nu}\coloneqq\text{diag}\left(-1,-1,+1,+1\right).
\]

\end_inset

Klein space is reviewed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "barrett1994kleinian,bhattacharjee2022celestial,crawley2022black,duary2024spectral,klein1870theorie,plucker1865xvii,penrose1984spinors"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{K}^{4}\coloneqq\big(\mathbf{R}^{4},h_{\mu\nu}\big)$
\end_inset

.
 We endow this background with a gauge group 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{G}$
\end_inset

.
 Its Lie algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}\simeq\left(T_{e}\left(\mathbf{G}\right),[\cdot,\cdot]\right)$
\end_inset

 is assumed compact and semi-simple.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathsf{T}^{\mathsf{a}}\}$
\end_inset

 be a basis of generators satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathsf{T}^{\mathsf{a}},\mathsf{T}^{\mathsf{b}}]=if^{\mathsf{abc}}\mathsf{T}^{\mathsf{c}}$
\end_inset

,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\mathsf{abc}}$
\end_inset

 the structure constants.
 We choose the trace normalisation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Tr}\left(\mathsf{T}^{\mathsf{a}}\mathsf{T}^{\mathsf{b}}\right)=2^{-1}\boldsymbol{k}^{\mathsf{ab}}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}^{\mathsf{ab}}$
\end_inset

 is the Cartan-Killing form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We study tree-level scattering of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 gluons in a next-to-maximal-helicity-violating (
\begin_inset Formula $N^{1}$
\end_inset

-MHV) configuration.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{1}$
\end_inset

-MHV superamplitude depends on spinor momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{i}^{A},\bar{\nu}_{i\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 and Grassmann variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha=1,2,3,4\right)$
\end_inset

 encoding helicity degrees of freedom.
 It takes the form
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For a review,
 see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "brandhuber2011tree,elvang2013scattering,badger2024scattering"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{A}_{n}^{\mathsf{a_{1}...a_{n}}}\left(\nu_{i}^{A},\bar{\nu}_{i\dot{A}},\eta_{i}^{\alpha}\right)\,=\,\left(2\pi\right)^{4}\delta^{4|0}\big(P^{A\dot{A}}\big)\delta^{0|8}\big(Q^{\alpha\dot{A}}\big)\,A_{n}^{\mathsf{a_{1}...a_{n}}}\left(\nu_{i}^{A},\bar{\nu}_{i\dot{A}},\eta_{i}^{\alpha}\right).\label{eq:-3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,...,n$
\end_inset

 labels the external gluons.
 The total four-momentum and supercharge are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P^{A\dot{A}}\,\coloneqq\,\sum_{i=1}^{n}\,\nu_{i}^{A}\bar{\nu}_{i}^{\dot{A}},\,\,\,Q^{\alpha A}\,\coloneqq\,\sum_{i=1}^{n}\,\nu_{i}^{A}\,\eta_{i}^{\alpha}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Dual Coordinates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To express the 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{1}$
\end_inset

-MHV superamplitude,
 we introduce dual (zone) coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}^{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

.
 These solve the momentum-conserving delta function 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{4|0}\big(P^{A\dot{A}}\big)$
\end_inset

 via:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{i}^{A\dot{A}}-y_{i+1}^{A\dot{A}}\coloneqq\nu_{i}^{A}\bar{\nu}_{i}^{\dot{A}}.\label{eq:-9}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i<j\leq n$
\end_inset

,
 set:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{ij}^{A\dot{A}}\coloneqq y_{i}^{A\dot{A}}-y_{j}^{A\dot{A}},\,\,\,y_{ji}^{A\dot{A}}\coloneqq-y_{ij}^{A\dot{A}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Dual Conformal Invariant
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{1}$
\end_inset

-MHV superamplitude admits a representation in terms of a dual-conformal 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-invariant
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For a discussion of dual conformal symmetry,
 see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "drummond2008planar,mason2010complete,alday2008scattering,henn2009duality,korchemsky2010superconformal,alday2007gluon,brandhuber2008mhv"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This invariant takes the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R_{n;ab}\big(\nu_{i}^{A},\bar{\nu}_{i\dot{A}},\eta_{i}^{\alpha}\big)\,\,=\,\frac{\left\langle \nu_{a-1},\nu_{a}\right\rangle \,\left\langle \nu_{b-1},\nu_{b}\right\rangle \,\delta^{0|4}\big(\varXi^{\alpha}\big)}{y_{ab}^{2}\,\langle\nu_{n}|y_{nb}y_{ba}^{-1}|\nu_{a-1}\rangle\,\langle\nu_{n}|y_{nb}y_{ba}^{-1}|\nu_{a}\rangle\,\langle\nu_{n}|y_{na}y_{ab}^{-1}|\nu_{b-1}\rangle\,\langle\nu_{n}|y_{na}y_{ab}^{-1}|\nu_{b}\rangle},\label{eq:-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Xi^{\alpha}\big(\nu_{i}^{A},\bar{\nu}_{i\dot{A}},\eta_{i}^{\alpha}\big)\,\coloneqq\,\sum_{i=1}^{a-1}\,\langle\nu_{n}|y_{nb}y_{ba}^{-1}|\nu_{i}\rangle\,\eta_{i}^{\alpha}\,+\,\sum_{i=1}^{b-1}\,\langle\nu_{n}|y_{na}y_{ab}^{-1}|\nu_{i}\rangle\,\eta_{i}^{\alpha}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Celestial Description.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To pass from momentum-space amplitudes to their celestial-basis form,
 we introduce a normalised set of van der Waerden spinors 
\begin_inset Formula $\{z_{i}^{A},\bar{z}_{i\dot{A}}\}$
\end_inset

 on the celestial torus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{CT}$
\end_inset

.
 These are defined by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z_{i}^{A}\,\coloneqq\,\left(1,-\zeta_{i}\right),\,\,\,\bar{z}_{i\dot{A}}\,\coloneqq\,\left(1,-\bar{\zeta}_{i}\right),\label{eq:-98}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{i},\bar{\zeta}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are planar coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{CT}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}>0$
\end_inset

 the frequency of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th gluon.
 We reparametrise the spinor momenta via:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nu_{i}^{A}\,\mapsto\,z_{i}^{A},\,\,\,\bar{\nu}_{i\dot{A}}\,\mapsto\,s_{i}\,\bar{z}_{i\dot{A}}.\label{eq:-24}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Applying these replacements to the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-invariant (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-2"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) yields its celestial form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R_{n;ab}=\frac{\langle z_{a-1},z_{a}\rangle\langle z_{b-1},z_{b}\rangle\delta^{0|4}\big(\Theta^{\alpha}\big)}{y_{ab}^{2}\langle z_{n}|y_{nb}y_{ba}^{-1}|z_{a-1}\rangle\langle z_{n}|y_{nb}y_{ba}^{-1}|z_{a}\rangle\langle z_{n}|y_{na}y_{ab}^{-1}|z_{b-1}\rangle\langle z_{n}|y_{na}y_{ab}^{-1}|z_{b}\rangle},\label{eq:-4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Theta^{\alpha}\left(u^{A},v^{B}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\sum_{i=1}^{a-1}\,\langle u,z_{i}\rangle\,\eta_{i}^{\alpha}\,+\,\sum_{j=1}^{b-1}\,\langle v,z_{j}\rangle\,\eta_{j}^{\alpha}.\label{eq:-5}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Fadde'ev-Popov Representation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Fadde'ev-Popov-Method-N-MHV"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our objective is to find the Mellin transform of the gluonic superamplitude (Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-3"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

)).
 This yields the celestial amplitude:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{\mathcal{A}}_{n}^{\mathsf{a_{1}...a_{n}}}\big(z_{i}^{A},\bar{z}_{i\dot{A}},\eta_{i}^{\alpha}\big).
\]

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-invariant in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-3"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) depends nonlinearly on the frequencies 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 through the dual coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}^{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

.
 This nonlinearity obstructs a direct Mellin transform.
 To overcome this difficulty,
 we recast the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-invariant via the Fadde'ev-Popov procedure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our aim is an integral representation in which all 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

-dependence is isolated into delta functions.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}\,\coloneqq\,\mathbf{R}^{2}\times\mathbf{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 be the integration domain.
 We introduce coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{A'}\,\coloneqq\,\big(u^{A},v^{B}\big)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{A}$
\end_inset

 are van der Waerden spinors and 
\begin_inset Formula $A'\in\{A,B\}$
\end_inset

.
 The orientation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 is given by the Lebesgue measure:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d^{4}U\,\coloneqq\,d^{2}u\wedge d^{2}v.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Observe that the reality of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 follows from the Kleinian signature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We localise the Fadde'ev-Popov integral on a constraint subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}\subset\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

.
 To define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}$
\end_inset

,
 consider the auxiliary spinor functions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{n;ab}^{A}\big(y_{i}^{B\dot{B}}\big)\,\coloneqq\,z_{n}^{B}\,\left(y_{nb}\right)_{B\dot{B}}\,(y_{ba}^{-1})^{A\dot{B}},\label{eq:-6}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{n;ab}^{A}\big(y_{i}^{B\dot{B}}\big)\,\coloneqq\,z_{n}^{B}\,(y_{na})_{B\dot{B}}\,(y_{ab}^{-1})^{A\dot{B}}.\label{eq:-90}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}$
\end_inset

 is the set of points 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{A'}\in\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 satisfying:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u^{A}=f_{n;ab}^{A}\big(y_{i}^{B\dot{B}}\big),\,\,\,v^{A}=g_{n;ab}^{A}\big(y_{i}^{B\dot{B}}\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The corresponding constraint delta distribution is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta_{\mathscr{C}}\big(U^{A'}\big)\,\coloneqq\,\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(u^{A}-f_{n;ab}^{A}\big(y_{i}^{B\dot{B}}\big)\big)\,\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(v^{A}-g_{n;ab}^{A}\big(y_{i}^{B\dot{B}}\big)\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With these ingredients,
 the Fadde'ev-Popov representation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-invariant reads:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R_{n;ab}\,=\,\frac{1}{y_{ab}^{2}}\,\underset{\mathcal{I}\,\,\,\,\,}{\int}\,d^{4}U\,\,\,\mathcal{F}_{ab}\big(U^{A'}\big)\,\delta^{0|4}\big(\Theta^{\alpha}\big)\,\delta_{\mathscr{C}}\big(U^{A'}\big),\label{eq:-88}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F}_{ab}\big(U^{A'}\big)\,\coloneqq\,\frac{\langle z_{a-1},z_{a}\rangle\langle z_{b-1},z_{b}\rangle}{\langle z_{a-1},u\rangle\langle u,z_{a}\rangle\langle z_{b-1},v\rangle\langle v,z_{b}\rangle}.\label{eq:-145}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This representation makes the 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

-dependence factor through the constraint delta function 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\mathscr{C}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Delta Functions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Delta-Functions-N-MHV"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now expand the delta functions in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-88"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) using their integral representations.
 We express them in terms of the celestial coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}^{A}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{z}_{i\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Fermionic Delta Function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1,...,4$
\end_inset

 index the supersymmetry generators,
 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 be a Grassmann variable.
 In superanalysis,
 one defines:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta^{0|4}\big(\varepsilon^{\alpha}\big)\,\coloneqq\,\bigwedge_{\alpha=1}^{4}\,\varepsilon^{\alpha}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In terms of a Berezin integral
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "berezin2013introduction"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dewitt1992supermanifolds"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "leites1980introduction"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "manin1997introduction"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta^{0|4}\big(\varepsilon^{\alpha}\big)\,=\,\underset{\mathbf{R}^{0|4}\,\,\,}{\int}\,d^{0|4}\chi\,\,\,\exp\left(i\chi\cdot\varepsilon\right),\,\,\,\chi\cdot\varepsilon\,\coloneqq\,\chi_{\alpha}\varepsilon^{\alpha}.\label{eq:-89}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Substituting Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-5"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) into Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-89"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) then yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta^{0|4}\left(\Theta^{\alpha}\right)\,=\,\underset{\mathbf{R}^{0|4}\,\,\,}{\int}\,d^{0|4}\chi\,\,\,\bigwedge_{i=1}^{a-1}\,\,\,\exp\left(i\left\langle u,z_{i}\right\rangle \chi\cdot\eta_{i}\right)\,\,\,\bigwedge_{j=a}^{b-1}\,\,\,\exp\left(i\left\langle v,z_{j}\right\rangle \chi\cdot\eta_{j}\right).\label{eq:-14}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Bosonic Delta Function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A}$
\end_inset

 be a real van der Waerden spinor.
 The spinor delta function admits the integral representation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}^{2}\left(\lambda^{A}\right)\,=\,\underset{\mathbf{R}^{2}\,\,\,}{\int}\,\frac{d^{2}\sigma}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\,\exp\left(i\left\langle \lambda\sigma\right\rangle \right).\label{eq:-102}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By substituting Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-6"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) into this representation,
 one obtains:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(u^{A}-f_{n;ab}^{A}\big(y_{i}^{B\dot{B}}\big)\big)\,=\,\underset{\mathbf{R}^{2}\,\,\,}{\int}\,\frac{d^{2}\hat{u}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\,\,\,\exp\big(i\,\langle z_{n}|y_{nb}y_{ba}^{-1}|\hat{u}\rangle\big)\,e^{-i\langle u|\hat{u}\rangle}.\label{eq:-7}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Similarly,
 substituting Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-90"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) into Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-102"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(v^{A}-g_{n;ab}^{A}\big(y_{i}^{B\dot{B}}\big)\big)\,=\,\underset{\mathbf{R}^{2}\,\,\,}{\int}\frac{d^{2}\hat{v}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\,\,\,\exp\left(i\,\langle z_{n}|y_{na}y_{ab}^{-1}|\hat{v}\rangle\right)\,e^{-i\langle v|\hat{v}\rangle}.\label{eq:-8}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Next,
 introduce the change of integration variables:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{u}^{\dot{A}}\,\coloneqq\,\hat{u}_{A}\left(y_{ba}^{-1}\right)^{A\dot{A}},\,\,\,\tilde{v}^{\dot{A}}\,\coloneqq\,\hat{v}_{A}\left(y_{ab}^{-1}\right)^{A\dot{A}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It follows that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(u^{A}-f_{n;ab}^{A}\big(y_{i}^{B\dot{B}}\big)\big)\,=\,\left|y_{ba}^{2}\right|\,\underset{\mathbf{R}^{2}\,\,\,}{\int}\,\frac{d^{2}\tilde{u}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\,\,\,\exp\left(i\,\langle z_{n}|y_{nb}|\tilde{u}]\right)\,\exp\left(-i\,\langle u|y_{ba}|\tilde{u}]\right),\label{eq:-10}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(v^{A}-g_{n;ab}^{A}\big(y_{i}^{B\dot{B}}\big)\big)\,=\,\left|y_{ab}^{2}\right|\,\underset{\mathbf{R}^{2}\,\,\,}{\int}\frac{d^{2}\tilde{v}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\,\,\,\exp\left(i\,\langle z_{n}|y_{na}|\tilde{v}]\right)\,\exp\left(-i\,\langle v|y_{ab}|\tilde{v}]\right).\label{eq:-11}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 employing the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}^{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-9"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 one expands the bosonic delta functions in the celestial parametrisation 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}^{A},\bar{z}_{i\dot{A}},\eta_{i}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(u^{A}-f_{n;ab}^{A}\big(y_{i}^{B\dot{B}}\big)\big)\,=\,\left|y_{ba}^{2}\right|\,\underset{\mathbf{R}^{2}\,\,\,}{\int}\,\frac{d^{2}\tilde{u}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\,\,\,\prod_{i=a}^{b-1}\,\exp\left(-is_{i}\,\langle z_{i}|u\tilde{u}|\bar{z}_{i}]\right)\,\,\,\prod_{i=b}^{n}\,\exp\left(is_{i}\,\langle z_{i}|z_{n}\tilde{u}|\bar{z}_{i}]\right),\label{eq:-12}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(v^{A}-g_{n;ab}^{A}\big(y_{i}^{B\dot{B}}\big)\big)\,=\,\left|y_{ab}^{2}\right|\,\underset{\mathbf{R}^{2}\,\,\,}{\int}\,\frac{d^{2}\tilde{v}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{2}}\,\,\,\prod_{i=a}^{b-1}\,\exp\left(is_{i}\langle z_{i}|z_{n}\tilde{v}+v\tilde{v}|\bar{z}_{i}]\right)\,\,\,\prod_{i=b}^{n}\,\exp\left(is_{i}\langle z_{i}|z_{n}\tilde{v}|\bar{z}_{i}]\right).\label{eq:-13}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Integral Representation for the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-invariant
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Integral-Representation-for"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Fadde'ev-Popov-Method-N-MHV"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we applied the Fadde'ev-Popov method to the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-invariant,
 noting that all dependence on the frequency parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 is carried by delta functions.
 In Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Delta-Functions-N-MHV"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we then expanded each delta function in the spinor basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{z_{i}^{A},\bar{z}_{i\dot{A}}\}$
\end_inset

 and the Grassmann variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 By combining these two steps,
 we arrive at the final form of the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-invariant,
 which we now discuss just before performing the Mellin transform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Integration Superdomain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin by defining the 
\emph on
parameter superspace
\emph default
 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{P}\,\coloneqq\,\mathbf{R}^{8|4}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This supermanifold is globally charted by the coordinates:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau^{M}\,\coloneqq\,\big(u^{A},v^{B},\tilde{u}_{\dot{A}},\tilde{v}_{\dot{B}},\chi^{\alpha}\big),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the abstract index 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 ranges over 
\begin_inset Formula $\{A,B,\dot{A},\dot{B},\chi^{\alpha}\}$
\end_inset

.
 We shall refer to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{M}$
\end_inset

 as the 
\emph on
moduli parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The canonical orientation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 is provided by the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

-graded volume form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d^{8|4}\tau\,\coloneqq\,d^{2}u\wedge d^{2}v\wedge d^{2}\tilde{u}\wedge d^{2}\tilde{v}\wedge d^{0|4}\chi.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Embedding Coordinates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following subsections,
 we shall construct the moduli superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{M}_{3}$
\end_inset

,
 which parametrises the configuration of three minitwistor lines on which the amplitude localises.
 For now,
 we regard 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{M}_{3}$
\end_inset

 as an abstract supermanifold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each gluon 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,...,n$
\end_inset

 participating in the scattering process,
 we associate a copy 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{i}$
\end_inset

 of the parameter superspace,
 which may be viewed as a submanifold of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{M}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The embedding coordinates adapted to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are defined as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let the index 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 run over the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

.
 We introduce the family of coordinate functions on the parameter superspace:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathsf{Q}_{\ell}^{K}\coloneqq\big(\mathcal{Q}_{\ell}^{A\dot{A}},q_{\ell}^{\alpha A}\big):\mathcal{P}\longrightarrow\mathbf{R}^{4|8},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

whose components are listed in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Embedding-coordinates--N-MHV"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
